<head>
<title>Peruvian Hostage Crisis - ENN Continued Reports</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p align=left>ENN PERU SITREP<br>
Excerpted from ENN Daily Report -12/24/96 -Vol. 2, No.359<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>HOSTAGE CRISIS GOES INTO ITS FIRST WEEK ...</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br><IMG SRC="/peruhi.gif" align=right>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - A man claiming to be the international spokesman for the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement 
(MRTA) spoke to CNN from Hamburg, Germany, on Monday. He indicated that the MRTA would never surrender to 
authorities.<br>
<br>
In the interview, Issac Velazco said, &quot;Effectively, what the government of President Fujimori is asking is that the group 
gives up. The word surrender of capitulation is not in the vocabulary of the Tupac Amaru soldier.&quot;<br>
<br>
A woman claiming to be the wife of Velazco earlier on Monday called a Paraguayan radio station from Hamburg. She said 
that the MRTA was planning more attacks against the Peruvian government.<br>
<br>
Peruvian police sources confirmed that they believe another MRTA terrorist cell is at large in Lima and could attack if 
negotiations falter or go sour. One police source said, &quot;If police storm the Embassy, it is possible they will start car bomb 
attacks or other sabotage.&quot;<br>
<br>
The Red Cross reports that there has been no negotiations between the terrorists and authorities since Sunday.<br>
<br>
Peruvian officials are also trying to establish the real identity of seven of the 225 men who were freed on Sunday night. 
Seven names do not match those on a master list of hostages to be freed. There is a theory that an MRTA terrorist may 
have slipped out with the freed captives.<br>
<br>
President Fujimori and Interior Minister General Juan Briones Davila visited the scene at the Japanese ambassador's 
residence on Monday. They did not, however, get out of their bulletproof automobiles.<br>
<br>
A doctor, who has scene the hostages, reports that the unhealthy conditions inside of the Japanese ambassador's house has 
caused at least eight cases of eye infections and an outbreak of diarrhea.<br>
<br>
There was a report on Monday that cited Peruvian anti-terrorist police saying that the Lima attack was financed by ransom 
money obtained by the MRTA in 1995. The MRTA kidnapped a Bolivian businessman and held him captive for 46 days 
until a ransom of $1.2 million was paid. Throughout its 14-year history, MRTA has kept strong links with militants in 
Bolivia. The terrorists go back-and-forth between the two countries and several MRTA rebels are jailed in Bolivia.<br>
</p>
<p><font size=5><strong>FORMER MRTA HOSTAGE DEBRIEFED ...</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - Carlos Aquino Rodriguez, age 37, a university economics professor, was among the 225 men 
who were released by the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement terrorists on Sunday night.<br>
<br>
Aquino said that last Tuesday evening he had been enjoying the lavish party at the Japanese ambassador's residence when 
it was suddenly interrupted by an explosion. He said, &quot;Suddenly, at about 8:20 p.m. there was a tremendous explosion 
which stood everybody's hair on end and created total panic.&quot;<br>
<br>
The terrorists later told him how they had accomplished off their daring attack by dynamiting the wall of a house abutting 
the rear of the Japanese compound. He said that reports of terrorists infiltrating the party dressed as waiters was not true. 
Aquino said, &quot;That's not the case, they came shooting in the air and yelling. It was terrifying.&quot;<br>
<br>
The terrorists carefully censored their captives and divided them into different groups after the initial release of the women 
and the elderly. The hostages were divided by military officers, politicians and government officials, businessmen and 
diplomats. Aquino was placed into a group with other professionals.<br>
<br>
Aquino said that 28 people in his group were herded into a 12-foot by 18-foot bedroom. The hostages were closely 
guarded by heavily armed terrorists who were dressed in commando uniforms. They communicated with one another via 
two-way radio on a constant basis. He said, &quot;There was always one of them at the door. The idea was for us to be 
permanently watched.&quot;<br>
<br>
The only time Aquino said that he felt in danger for his life was during the first few hours of the siege when the terrorists 
were battling with police on the outside of the compound. He said, &quot;We suffered no physical or mental harm.&quot;<br>
<br>
Aquino spoke twice to terrorist leader Nestor Cerpa. He said that he grew to respect Cerpa. Aquino described Cerpa in 
this way: &quot;He explained his strategy and what his movement wanted ... My personal opinion is that he is a cultured man, 
well-read and quite intelligent.&quot;<br>
<br>
It is the opinion of Aquino that the MRTA did not merely seize the Japanese ambassador's residence as a publicity stunt. 
He described the mood of the terrorists when he left as: &quot;When we were saying good-bye, they said that they were ready 
for any military attack and were not in the least bit afraid.&quot;</p>
<hr>
<p><font size=3>Excerpted from ENN Daily Report - 12/25/96 - Vol. 2, No. 360</font></p>
<p><font size=5><strong>URUGUAY APPARENTLY CONCEDES TO THE DEMANDS OF 
MRTA TERRORISTS</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - A new estimated number of 105 hostages still remain inside the residence of the Japanese 
ambassador in Lima. They are being held captive by at least 20 terrorists who are members of the Tupac Amaru 
Revolutionary Movement (MRTA).<br>
<br>
The latest hostage to be released was the Uruguayan ambassador. Ambassador Tabre Bocalandro was released on 
Christmas Eve. The ambassador was freed after a Uruguayan appeals court released two members of the Tupac Amaru, 
who had been jailed in that country. It is widely believed that the release of the two rebels is a concession to the MRTA. 
The judge that ordered the release of the two rebels insisted that his decision had nothing whatsoever to do with the 
captivity of his country's ambassador.<br>
<br>
A very unhappy Peru ordered its acting ambassador in Uruguay to return home in protest to the release of the two MRTA 
militants. It is believed that the Peruvians may think that Uraguay has &quot;undercut&quot; their bargaining position.<br>
<br>
The two released MRTA rebels were identified as Luis Alberto Samaniego and Silvia Gora Rivera. They were arrested by 
Uraguayan authorities for having fake Bolivian passports in their possession.</p>
<hr>
<p><font size=3>Excerpted from ENN Daily Report - 12/26/96 - Vol. 2, No. 261</font></p>
<p><font size=5><strong>LOUD EXPLOSION ROCKS JAPANESE COMPOUND ...</strong></font><font size=3><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - A loud explosion early on Thursday rocked the residence of the Japanese ambassador in Lima, 
where 104 hostages are being held by members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA). This is the ninth 
day of the hostage crisis.<br>
<br>
A policeman, at the scene, said, &quot;The explosion came from within the residence at the back part. We are trying to 
investigate it, but we cannot get very close.&quot;<br>
<br>
The explosion occurred at about 1:45 a.m. from inside the grounds of the residence behind the building where the captives 
are located. No injuries have been reported and no damage was seen to the house. It is uncertain if the blast was triggered 
by accident or if it was deliberate. Police estimated that the explosion was equal to about four sticks of dynamite.<br>
<br>
There was an unconfirmed report that two men were seen fleeing from the residence compound over nearby roofs shortly 
after the blast. These men may have been Peruvian anti-terrorist police conducting a recon mission and were spotted and 
warned off by the terrorists with the explosion.<br>
<br>
The blast came only hours after the MRTA terrorists released the sick, 34-year-old, first secretary of the Japanese 
Embassy in Peru. This brought the known total of hostages still being held to 104.<br>
<br>
There is a speculation that a behind-the-scenes deal may be worked out that will allow the MRTA terrorists to fly to 
asylum in Cuba after releasing the hostages. The reliability of this information is untested.<br>
<br>
Another rumor that is circulating is that Malaysia may attempt to cut a deal with the terrorists in order to secure freedom 
for its ambassador to Peru. Again, the source of this information is considered to be untested.<br>
</font></p>
<p><font size=5><strong>PROFILE OF MRTA LEADER NESTOR CERPA ...</strong></font><font size=3><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - The leader of the terrorists who took over the residence of the Japanese ambassador has been 
identified as 48- year-old Nestor Cerpa. Cerpa, a long-time member of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement 
(MRTA).<br>
<br>
Cerpa is no stranger to the people and authorities of Peru. He is physically described as a stocky man of medium height. 
Cerpa walks with a slight limp with his right leg -- this limp was possibly caused by a wound in battle. He has a long, thin<br>
mustache and a week's worth of stubble on his chin. Cerpa is said to have &quot;deep, dark eyes.&quot; He wears a red-and-white<br>
bandanna with his green combat fatigues.<br>
<br>
All of the hostages who have been debriefed has described Cerpa in the same manner. Ramiro Validivia called Cerpa 
&quot;decisive and focused ... a very professional person. He has tried to appear completely diplomatic and educated.&quot;<br>
Kieran Metcalfe, a Canadian mining executive said Cerpa was &quot;a very articulate and committed individual.&quot;<br>
<br>
Cerpa was born and raised in a working class neighborhood of Lima. He is said to have had little higher education. He first 
gained national attention about 18 years ago, when as a union leader he led 50 workers in the occupation of a textile 
factory. The union protested low wages and massive layoffs. Cerpa and the workers occupied the factory for more than 
six weeks before the Peruvian government ordered the police on 4 February 1979 to raid the plant. Their was a battle in 
which one policeman and three workers were killed.<br>
<br>
Following the clash, Cerpa was sentenced to serve almost a year for his part in the occupation. After being released and 
before going underground in the early 1980s, Cerpa became involved in leftist politics for a brief time.<br>
He became a member of Tupac Amaru and police say that he was personally behind the kidnappings of many business 
executives during the 1980s. The ransom money that was received helped finance the operations of the MRTA.<br>
<br>
The Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement is modeled after the Cuban revolutionary movement of Fidel Castro. The 
group does not consider itself communist or Marxist. They have also maintained their distance from Peru's largest terrorist<br>
organization -- the fanatical Maoist Shining Path. Counterterrorism experts estimate that the MRTA has about 200<br>
followers. That figure is down from a high of 1,000 in 1989. The group does have a leftist ideology. It opposes the free-<br>
market reforms of President Alberto Fujimori. MRTA says that the reforms only benefit the rich in Peru.<br>
<br>
Peruvian anti-terrorism police said that Cerpa has also been known as &quot;Comrade Evaristo.&quot; In 1985, he began a series of 
attacks, takeovers and kidnappings. A Lima newspaper was taken over in November of 1985. Before a number of 
photographers, the leader of the group took off his hood -- it was Nestor Cerpa.<br>
<br>
In 1992, the founder and leader of the MRTA Victor Polay and his second-in-command, Peter Cardenas, were arrested 
by Peruvian authorities. With their capture, Cerpa became the leader of the group's military operations.<br>
<br>
The first person to identify Cerpa as the leader of the terrorists who took over the residence of the Japanese ambassador 
was leftist Peruvian Congressman Javier Diez Canseco. Canseco said that Cerpa was looking to reach a settlement 
through negotiations -- but that he was still a military commando.<br>
</font></p>
<hr>
<p><font size=3>Excerpted from ENN Daily Report - 12/27/96 - Vol. 2, No. 362</font></p>
<p><font size=5><strong>Strategy Becoming Clearer; Political Concessions Continue</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor</p>
<p>LIMA. PERU (ENN) - The strategy of the Tupac Amaru terrorists is becoming clearer. On Thursday, Guatemalan 
Ambassador Jose Maria Argueta was released from captivity from the residence of the Japanese ambassador. It was said 
that he was freed because Guatemala had recently signed an agreement that ended a 36-year civil war with leftist guerrillas. 
Appearances would suggest that there may be a quid-pro-quo in the release of hostages and political acts by affected 
governments.<br>
<br>
All of the hostages who have been released say the same thing: the terrorists have treated their captives cordially and with 
respect. They have given the image of civility. There are still 103 hostages being held, including five ambassadors. The 
ambassadors still being held are from: Japan, Bolivia, the Dominican Republic, Honduras and Malaysia. <br>
<br>
It is known that four members of the MRTA are in prison in Bolivia. One freed hostage reported that he heard terrorist 
leader Nestor Cerpa tell Bolivia's ambassador: &quot;You're staying with me until the end.&quot; A Bolivian government spokesman 
said on Thursday that his government had no intention to giving in the pressure from the MRTA and will not release the 
four &quot;terrorists&quot; in exchange for their ambassador.<br>
<br>
NBC News on Thursday reported that a plan does exist to forcibly end the hostage crisis if necessary with an assault by 
elite police units from Peru and Japan. These police units are said to be currently training in a crude replica of the 
compound located in a remote part of Peru.<br>
<br>
A highly-placed Peruvian police official denied the claim that Japanese and Peruvian police are training together for such an 
assault. Japan, however, did send a small number of special police officers to take photographs of the compound on 24 
December.<br>
<br>
It is the opinion of counterterrorism experts, who have spoken to ENN, that if Peruvian and Japanese officials are planning 
such an assault -- they would be much better off if they were to allow &quot;experts&quot; from either the U.S., Great Britain or 
Germany to carry out such a plan. All three nations have reportedly offered their assistance in the matter. </p>
<p>Counterterrorism units from SFOD-Delta, the SAS Counterrevolutionary Warfare Wing and the German GSG-9 prepare 
themselves for this typical scenario on a constant basis and are better prepared to deal with this type of incident than any 
units that can be put together by Peru and Japan. Lives are at stake and geo-political pride should not get in the way, but it 
is still unlikely that non-Peruvian units will participate, excpet in an advisory capacity.<br>
</p>
All materials (C) Copyrighted by EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved. Contact ENN for permission to redistribute.
