<head>
<title>MTRA Take-Over of Japanese Compound in Peru</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>ENN FLASH Traffic 12/17/96 - 22:47CST<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>Revolutionary Group Takes Over Japanese Residence in Lima, Peru</strong></font><br>
By C.L. Staten, ERRI Senior Analyst<br>
<br>
(ENN) Preliminary and as yet, partially unconfirmed, information would indicate that the Japanese Ambassador's residence 
in Lima, Peru has been taken over by the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA). As many as 40 people, 
including diplomats have reportedly been taken hostage and an armed barricade situation is reportedly on-going at this 
hour.<br>
<br>
According to local witnesses, a group of approximately 20 men, armed with automatic rifles and grenade launchers, 
stormed the home at approximately 20:00p.m. (local time) on Tuesday night. It is believed that Japanese ambassador 
Morihisa Aoki, Peru's foreign minister Francisco Tuleda, and the ambassadors from Brazil, Spain, and Cuba may also be 
held by the guerillas.<br>
<br>
According to a Lima radio station, a spokesperson for the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement called them to claim 
responsibility for taking the hostages. The guerillas threatened to kill all of the dignitaries, unless Peruvian authorities 
released their compatriots from prison. The spokesman also allegedly called for negotiations with the government, to be 
held publicly on live television and radio.<br>
<br>
The onset of the attack on the residence was reportedly punctuated by several powerful explosions and gunfire was heard 
between security personnel and the guerillas. It is unknown, at this time, if any injuries or deaths occurred during the 
take-over.<br>
<br>
The situation near the residence is described as extremely tense as soldiers and special police units are positioned to 
surround it. The Peruvian government is said to be consulting at this hour with the various governments who have hostages 
inside the compound. This latest assault by the Amaru guerillas is viewed as a major escalation in their battle with the 
established government of Peru.<br>
<br>
ENN continues to monitor events in Lima and will provide additional updates as more become available.<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><font color="#FF0000"><font size=4><strong>Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA)</strong></font></font><br>
<br>
<font size=4>Description:</font><br>
<br>
Traditional Marxist-Leninist revolutionary movement in Peru, formed in 1983. Stated Objective; is to rid Peru--and 
perhaps the region--of &quot;imperialist&quot; influence and establish a Marxist regime.<br>
<br>
<font size=4>Activities:</font><br>
<br>
Responsible for more anti-US attacks than any other group in Latin America.<br>
<br>
* In 1990 and 1991, attacked the US Ambassador's<br>
residence, bombed the US Consulate and US-Peruvian Binational<br>
Center, attacked US businesses and Mormon churches.<br>
* Attacked Peru's Presidential Palace, and President Fujimori's airplane in 1991.<br>
* Took over United Press International Office in 1992 and forced them to transmit propaganda. Left behind bombs.<br>
* Attempted bombing of national legislature, 1995<br>
<br>
<font size=4>Strength : </font>1,000 combatants.<br>
<br>
<font size=4>Location/Area of Operation:</font> Peru. Occasionally, Bolivia in conjunction with the ELN.<br>
<br>
External Aid: Has received training in/from Cuba, but probably not in past 3-4 years. May have ties to Libya and has 
allegedly received funding and weapons from them. May receive funding from Columbian and Peruvian drug dealers in last 
2-3 years.<br>
<br>
<font size=4>ERRI Brief Analysis</font><br>
<br>
The MRTA has decreased in strength in recent years, following raids by anti-terrorist police and jail sentences for leaders. 
Political infighting within the group has also caused it to splinter and be less organized. Some counter-terrorist experts 
report that they thought MRTA was just about disbanded a year and a half ago. However, it is thought that members do 
still possess the training and equipment to carry out some operations.<br>
<br>
<em>Source: United States Department of State Terrorism Reports, and Emergency Response &amp; Research Archives</em><br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>09:00CST - 12/18/96<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>TERRORIST SIEGE IN PERU</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor and C. L. Staten, Senior Analyst<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - Rebels from the Peruvian Tupac Amaru movement staged a well-executed, military-style raid 
upon the house of the Japanese ambassador on Tuesday night. Explosions were heard and gunfire was exchanged with 
police for almost hour.<br>
<br>
At the end of the initial clash the guerrillas had taken control of a compound the covers an entire block and sits behind a 
15-foot high wall that is topped by a 10-foot electrical fence in Lima's San Isidro residential area. About 170 hostages, 
mostly women and elderly people, were released after a few hours of the assault. It is estimated that the rebels are still 
holding about 200 hostages.<br>
<br>
Among the hostages are the ambassadors from: Austria, Boliva, Brazil, Canada, Cuba, Germany, Japan, South Korea and 
Venezuela. As Well as the foreign and agriculture ministers of Peru, six Peruvian legislators, the president of Peru's 
Supreme Court and dozens of Japanese businessmen. It is reported that there are seven American citizens among the 
captives. Four of the Americans are said to work for the U.S Agency for International Development. The U.S. 
ambassador to Peru, Dennis Jett, reportedly left the Japanese ambassador's residence just before the armed guerrillas 
started their attack.<br>
<br>
Latest information indicates that 23 rebels, including three females, are in control of the compound. At least one guerrilla, 
believed to be a leader, has reportedly suffered a serious gunshot wound to the leg.<br>
<br>
The daring plan took place at about 8:00 p.m. on Tuesday night. A reception honoring Japanese Emperor Akihito's 
birthday was taking place. Peruvian police said that some of the guerrillas slipped past security by posing as waiters. 
Reportedly, a rocket was fired into the building and a shootout erupted. There were reports of rebels even scaling the walls 
of the residence. In the beginning of the drama, the hostages were gathered and told to lie face-down on the floor for about 
40 minutes.<br>
<br>
The rebels are calling their operation &quot;Breaking The Silence.&quot; On Wednesday morning, they claimed to hold 250 hostages. 
The MRTA guerrillas also said that they have laid explosive booby- traps at the entrances to the building.<br>
<br>
<font size=4>The Situation</font><br>
<br>
Witnesses described the hostage-takers as being dressed in black and armed with automatic weapons and grenades. They 
were said to be &quot;calm and determined.&quot;<br>
<br>
According to press reports, Peruvian police reportedly may have fired tear gas into the compound earlier today. If it 
happened, it may have been a mistake. The rebels were equipped with gas masks and the only people affected were the 
hostages.<br>
<br>
Early on Wednesday, the MRTA rebels threatened to kill the captives unless their demands were met. One rebel speaking 
to a local radio station by telephone said, &quot;We are clear -- the liberation of all our comrades or we die with all the 
hostages.&quot;<br>
<br>
The MRTA says that they have 400 to 500 of their comrades in Peruvian prisons and insist upon the release of them and 
their leader, Victor Polay, who has been serving a life sentence since 1992. The group also wants a review of Peru's 
judicial system and direct negotiations with the Peruvian government.<br>
<br>
One rebel said that the MRTA guerrillas want to be transported with their freed comrades to the group's &quot;war zone in the 
jungle.&quot;<br>
<br>
There have been several developments in the situation since mid-morning. At about 9:00 a.m. a loud explosion was heard 
and smoke could be seen from within the compound. This was followed by a number of shots. It is uncertain if the shots 
came from MRTA rebels, from inside the compound, or from police on the outside.</p>
<p>The rebels are demanding that Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori personally meet and negotiate with the hostge-takers. 
A guerrilla spokesman told a local radio station, &quot;The only thing I want to say is that the president must come and speak to 
us personally. Nothing will happen to him, we only want dialogue.&quot; The press, on the scene, did report that Fujimori was 
seen near the incident at mid-morning.<br>
<br>
It has been reported, by at least one media outlet that the rebels have set some sort of noon EST deadline for their 
demands to be met or they will start killing the hostages. It is unknown if MRTA has the wherewithall to carry out these 
threats.<br>
<br>
ENN has also received unconfirmed reports that there may have been a prison uprising this morning where some, if not 
many, of the MRTA prisoners are being held. It is not certain who is currently in control of that Peruvian prison. Additional 
information on this development is sketchy at the time of this report.<br>
<br>
Chile has reportedly tightened its security on its border with Peru &quot;to prevent members of the terrorist group from trying to 
enter Chile,&quot; according to Chile's interior minister.<br>
<br>
<font size=4>Errors and Omissions on Both Sides?</font><br>
<br>
One mistake that the hostage-takers would appear to have made is that they have allowed the hostages to make phone 
calls from within the embassy. This could prove to be a very good source of intelligence about what is happening inside, the 
numbers of hostage-takers, how they are armed, where they may be deployed inside the building and so forth. However, if 
the negotiations do not go the way that makes the rebels happy -- this source of intelligence will probably stop.<br>
<br>
However, Peruvian police have also been making their mistakes. Besides allegedly firing ineffectual tear gas into the 
compound, they have refused to send medical aid for two hostages and one rebel who have been wounded. The head of 
the Red Cross in Peru, who was on the scene shortly after dawn, confirmed that the government had not responded for the 
request for medical assistance.<br>
<br>
The Spanish Foreign Ministry has said that they have been asked by the guerrillas to send medical supplies inside the 
Japanese compound. Doing so could again afford counter-terrorist forces an an additional opportunity to collect data on 
the hostage takers. But, those kinds of decisions must be made by hostage negotiators.<br>
<br>
Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori, is the son of Japanese immigrants. It has been reported that he has been in close 
contact with Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, and that Fujimori is personally overseeing the negotiations with 
the rebels. Fujimori's mother was among the hostages who were freed. This was probably another mistake that was made 
by the rebels.<br>
<br>
In a call to Japan's NHK news service, the Japanese ambassador said that the hostage-takers wanted to talk directly to 
the President of Peru. Skillful negotiators will probably, however, attempt to prohibit direct contact between Fujimori and 
the hostage takers, as it restricts their options. The ambassador indicated that he was being held in a room by five or six 
rebels, whom he described as being young and armed with handguns and rifles.<br>
<br>
<font size=4>Military/HRU Response</font><br>
<br>
It would be Standard Operating Procedure (S.O.P.) that the U.S. Army's Delta Force counterterrorism unit would send 
operatives to act as observers in worldwide incidents such as this. This particularly true when American citizens are being 
held as captives, as is the case in Peru. Operatives from the British SAS may also be dispatched as observers, if there are 
British hostages involved. This is sometimes done with or without the permission or knowledge of the host government... in 
this case, Peru.<br>
<br>
It is also possible that a contingent of special forces operatives would also be forward deployed to Panama in order to be 
closer to the incident, should they be needed. However, it is the opinion of ERRI that the Peruvian government will most 
likely not request assistance from the United States or other governments. State department officials have already been 
quoted this morning as saying that Peru will take the lead in resolving the incident.<br>
<br>
The Hostage Rescue operational capabilities of the Peruvian counterterrorist units are not well known, although they have 
been involved in counter-narcotics and insurgency operations for several years. Many on the scene may be paramilitary 
troops/special police units, who are more familiar with jungle counterinsurgency operations, rather than a possible assault 
on a hostage-filled building in an urban area.<br>
<br>
ENN is closely monitoring the situation and at present is unable to predict the possible outcome of the situation. It is 
believed, however, that a &quot;period of crisis&quot; could come this afternoon, and again early tomorrow morning...if this situation is 
not peacefully resolved.<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>12/18/96 - 12:47CST</p>
<p><font size=5><strong>PERU HOSTAGE SITUATION UPDATE</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - The Tupac Amaru rebels who have taken between 200 and 300 hostages at the residence of the 
Japanese ambassador threatened to start killing their captives at 1220 EST today if their demands were not met.<br>
<br>
At noon EST, the commander of the rebel operation told Peruvian television, &quot;If in twenty minutes we do not have an 
answer we will begin to take our first victim and the first victim will be Foreign Minister Tudela (of Peru). We can't wait 
any longer.&quot;<br>
<br>
The guerrilla commander also said, &quot;Up to now there is no harm but within an hour they (the hostages) could suffer harm. 
We only give him (Fujimori) one hour more. If within an hour the president does not communicate with us he will see the 
results.<br>
<br>
ENN is closely watching the situation and as of 1345 EST no hostages have been known to be killed. There has been 
considerable activity seen around the compound. One person was seen to enter the residence. Police sharpshooters have 
taken positions all around the ambassador's residence.<br>
<br>
Several nations have reportedly urged the Peruvian government to do everything in their power to protect the hostages and 
not to use force against the guerrillas. These requests have come from countries with ambassadors inside of the building. 
An updated list indicates that the ambassador from Panama is among the hostages and possibly the ambassador from 
Spain.<br>
<br>
It was reported that a representative of the Red Cross was allowed by the guerrillas to enter the compound and negotiate 
with the rebels. The Red Cross representative said that he estimated that there were 300 people in the compound. It has 
been confirmed that among the hostages who were released after the initial attack were the sister and mother of Peru's 
President.<br>
<br>
At 9:00 a.m., what was believed to be a stick of dynamite was exploded on the patio of the residence by the rebels. There 
were no reports of any injuries.<br>
<br>
This attack by the Tupac Amaru movement seems to fall into the category of terrorism that has fallen into disuse in recent<br>
years by terrorist groups. The MRTA seems to want a lot of media coverage for their cause. They have been talking 
extensively to the local media and have allowed the Japanese ambassador to talk to Japan's NHK.<br>
<br>
Tupac Amaru lost much of its strength in recent years after most of its leaders and many of its members were captured and<br>
sent to prison. Peruvian police reported that they arrested five suspected rebels in the initial attack on Tuesday night.<br>
<br>
The Red Cross reported that besides wanting the release of their comrades from prison in Peru, they are also demanding<br>
the release of MRTA rebels being held outside of the country. It is believed that other Tupac Amaru rebels are 
incarcerated in Boliva and Uruguay.<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p>EmergencyNet NEWS Service<br>
ENN 12/18/96 - 1530 CST<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>MID-AFTERNOON UPDATE OF THE PERU HOSTAGE 
SITUATION</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
LIMA, PERU (ENN) - The first deadline set by the rebels who are holding a new estimated 490 hostages at the Japanese 
ambassador's residence has come and gone with no apparent bloodshed. The rebels, who are members of the Tupac 
Amaru Revolutionary Movement (MRTA), issued a 1220 EST deadline that passed with no apparent action taken.<br>
<br>
The MRTA rebels are still demanding the release of 400 to 500 imprisoned comrades, including their leader Victor Polay. 
They are also demanding safe passage to their hideaway in the jungles of Peru.<br>
<br>
Several countries with nationals being held are appealing for calm in handling the crisis. Spain has cautioned the Peruvian 
government that the use of force could lead to a massacre.<br>
<br>
While talking to Peruvian President Fujimori, Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar asked that Peru security forces 
employ psychological tactics against the guerrillas.<br>
<br>
Germany, whose ambassador is being held, offered Peru help in resolving the situation. German Foreign Minister Klaus 
Kinkel appealed to the Peruvian government to be prudent in its efforts.<br>
<br>
Panama has indicated that it believes that ambassadors and other diplomats from 18 different countries are being held 
captive, including diplomats from Great Britain, France and Poland.<br>
<br>
The British have confirmed that one member of their Embassy staff is among the hostages. The British Foreign Ministry has 
said that it has offered assistance to Peru. In a statement, the foreign ministry said, &quot;We stand ready to consider any 
request from the Peruvians for assistance.&quot; The British assistance could come in many forms.<br>
<br>
On Wednesday afternoon, a fax was sent from within the residence to the relatives of the hostages. The fax indicated that 
there may be as many as 490 hostages. The letter was signed by Peruvian Foreign Minister Francisco Tudela, Japanese 
Ambassador Morihisa Aoki and other ambassadors who are being held captive.<br>
<br>
The signatories of the fax said that they were speaking on the behalf of &quot;around 490 people, Peruvian citizens and officials, 
and foreign functionaries and diplomats.&quot; The letter also said, &quot;We believe it is indispensible to establish a dialogue. There 
are injured who require treatment.&quot; Four elderly men were reported released this afternoon by the rebels.<br>
<br>
In Canada, its foreign minister confirmed that up to 490 hostages were being held hostage. Canadian Foreign Minister 
Lloyd Axworthy said, &quot;Reports that we've had is that so far the hostages have been given proper treatment. We are clearly 
calling for moderation declared for those who are holding them captive. But at the same time, they've issued various 
demands that the Peruvian government release a number of their cohorts. I think a pretty fundamental principle is that to 
give in to those kind of demands simply exacerbates and increases the problem.&quot;<br>
<br>
Four Canadians are reported among the hostages. They include Anthony Vincent, the Canadian ambassador to Peru. 
Foreign Minister Axworthy added the Peruvian government has established a negotiating team, but it is uncertain what, if 
any, contact the team has had with the hostage-takers.</p>
