<head>
<title>Call For International Bio-War Inspections</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Excerpted from ENN Daily Report - 11/26/96 - Vol. 2, No. 331</p>
<p><font size=4><strong>Call For International Chemical/Biological WarfareVerification Program</strong></font><br>
By C.L. Staten, ERRI Senior Analyst<br>
<br>
(ENN) Washington, DC -- John Holum, Director of the U.S. Arms Control and Disarmament Agency, reportedly today 
will call for a formal biological weapon inspection system to be setup throughout the world. Mr. Holum, in a pre-release 
statement in Washington, said that the current state of the art in biotechnology could lead the world to a &quot;return to the dark 
ages.&quot; Holum's speech is to be presented today at the opening of a Geneva, Switzerland conference on the 1975 Biological 
Weapons Control Convention.<br>
<br>
&quot;Over-all, the United States believes that twice as many countries now have or are actively pursuing offensive biological 
weapons as when the original convention went into force,&quot; Holum's prepared text said. &quot;Now we face tyrants and terrorists 
who would return us to the dark ages...outlaws who share their predecessor's ancient depravity..but, with weapons that 
are frighteningly more modern,&quot; Holum added.<br>
<br>
According to the arms control agency in Washington, the original biological control convention did not include a provision 
that allowed on-site inspections of those suspected of producing offensive bio-weapons. Holum said that he hoped the 
most recent meetings addressed the issue and would provide for investigations into all cases of &quot;credible evidence&quot; of 
bio-weapon development or production.<br>
<br>
In closing, Holum's speech said, &quot;We can wait for a tragedy...for biological weapons to surpass what other weapons have 
done in Tokyo, Japn, Oklahoma City, or the Gulf War...Or, we can act now.&quot; Many, within anti-terrorism circles tell ENN 
that they sincerely hope that Mr. Holum's effort are successful. If not, they say they have serious concerns of a &quot;Biological 
Pearl Harbor&quot; in the coming decade.</p>
<p>(C) Copyright EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved -unauthorized redistribution is prohibited by law.</p>
