<head>
<title>White House Announces Zaire Deployment</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>ENN Instant Update 11/13/96 - 13:06CST<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>White House Announces U.S. Deployment to Zaire</strong></font><br>
By: C. L. Staten, Senior Analyst<br>
<br>
(ENN) White House spokesman Mike McCurry today announced that United States troops will join a multi-national 
military force, lead by Canada, which will provide &quot;humanitarian assistance&quot; to refugees in Zaire. According to McCurry, 
the situation in Zaire is reportedly &quot;rapidly deteriorating&quot; and as many as 1.2 million refugees may be at serious risk.<br>
<br>
Diplomats at the United Nations say that they expect a resolution, supporting the proposed multi-national force, to be 
passed within the &quot;next day or two.&quot; They indicate that there are many details to be worked out, but that they anticipate 
quick passage of such a resolution. As many as 12 nations are expected to participate in the effort, with a possibility of 
additional nations to be added in coming days.<br>
<br>
A U.S. military assessment team was reportedly dispatched to Uganda on Wednesday to begin to gain a better 
understanding of the needs &quot;on the ground&quot; in Eastern Zaire. They are expected to be followed immediately by 1,000 U.S. 
forces, many of whom will be dispatched to secure an airport near Goma.<br>
<br>
Senior military officials tell ENN that they are cognizant of the possibility of &quot;humanitarian disaster&quot; in Africa, unless some 
urgent international action is taken. But, there is also a concern among military leaders about American troops again 
becoming inextricably involved in a situation similar to Somalia, where American troops came under fire from guerilla 
forces. Reservations among the military are said to include having a well-defined mission, having an exit strategy, and 
implementing effective rules of engagement to protect the troops being dispatched to the area.<br>
<br>
Related reports from Rwanda and a number of other nearby countries indicate an increasing number of of &quot;firefights&quot;, 
artillery and mortar fire, and some rioting within the past 24 hours. Extremists in several areas have reportedly threatened 
aid workers and taken hostages. Instability across several borders, in the region, is said to be on-going at this time. Both 
media and relief personnel on the ground in Africa report that the situation there is &quot;fluid&quot; and &quot;chaotic.&quot;<br>
<br>
ENN continues to monitor the situation in Africa and will provide updates as the circumstances warrant.<br>
<br>
(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights reserved. Redistribution without permission is prohibited.</p>
