<head>
<title>Military/Police Spousal Abuse Law - No Guns</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p><font size=3>Excerpted from ENN Daily Report - 12/07/96 - Vol. 2, No. 342</font></p>
<p><font size=5><strong>FEDERAL LAW PROHIBITS OWNERSHIP, POSSESSION, OF 
GUNS AFTER CONVICTION OF DOMESTIC VIOLENCE 
MISDEMEANOR-- COPS, AGENTS, MILITARY, NOT EXEMPTED</strong></font><br>
<br>
By Jim Fay ENN Associate Editor<br>
<br>
In a little discussed amendment to a Federal appropriations bill, the United States Congress has passed a law that prohibits 
the ownership and possession of firearms by anyone convicted of a domestic violence crime, either felony or misdemeanor. 
However, nowhere in the law is there an exemption of police officers, federal agents, or even the military. This may cause a 
long-range ripple affect on criminal justice and defense operations.<br>
<br>
The law, originally entitled, &quot;H.R. 3756 - Treasury, Postal Service, and Government Appropriations Act, 1997,&quot; has been 
amended in the US Senate by US Senator Frank Lautenberg (D-NJ), with the assistance of Congressman (and US 
Senator- elect) Robert Torricelli (D-NJ), to include changes to various federal firearms laws to prohibit firearms in the<br>
possession of people convicted of domestic violence laws throughout the country. The law makes no exceptions or 
exemption.<br>
<br>
In addition, the law is retroactive to include all previous convictions for domestic violence.<br>
<br>
The law went into effect on September 30, and includes a wide range and obscure appropriations and amendments, 
including one involving a committee investigating the assassination of President John F. Kennedy, over thirty years ago.<br>
<br>
On November 26th, according to the Associated Press, a letter was transmitted to all law enforcement agencies from the 
Director of the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms, John Magaw, stating that all enforcement officers that have 
been convicted of domestic violence crimes, &quot;must immediately dispose of all firearms and ammunition in their possession.&quot; 
Also, the Department of Justice has ordered their enforcement agencies, which includes the FBI and the United States<br>
Marshal's Service, to have their agents that have agency-issued firearms, and have been convicted of domestic violence, to 
turn in their weapons to their supervisors.<br>
<br>
The affect this will have on the day-to-day operations of police agencies on all levels of government may be more that 
expected. Small agencies may have more than just one officer that was convicted of such crimes. These officers, although 
otherwise able to perform police work, will now be relegated to &quot;light-duty&quot; clerical positions, or, may, in fact, be 
terminated. A department with 12 officers, with two or three officers with domestic violence convictions over a period of 
time, will have almost 30% of the department out of service for just this one issue.<br>
<br>
Unlike sick leave, in which an officer is expected to return to full duty eventually, or light duty, prior to retirement due to 
illness or injury, there is no anticipated return to duty, or future use of the officer's position for a new hire, with these 
convictions. While a felony conviction prevents anyone from possessing a firearm automatically, misdemeanor convictions 
generally do not. Under this new federal law, all that is needed is a misdemeanor conviction for domestic violence to 
prohibit possession of a gun.<br>
<br>
One police officer told ENN that, prior to this most recent federal law, one department in the NYC area was forced to 
send a Department lawyer to a State Supreme Court to advise the Court that so many officers were restricted from 
carrying firearms due to Restraining Orders from accusing spouses and girlfriends, that it made the Department ineffective. 
The Department was able to convince the Court that it would be appropriate to have the officers carry weapons while on 
duty only, and turn them in at the end of their tour. Under the new federal law, even this is impossible.<br>
<br>
The Pentagon is also reportedly stymied by this new law, and is seeking the assistance of the Justice Department on how to 
initiate enforcement of it, according to the AP.<br>
<br>
The federal law will have at least two possible affects that were not anticipated by the sponsors of the legislation: one, a 
police agency (and the US military) will have an interest in every domestic violence case that involves one of their officers, 
since it will have long range affect on the agency and that officer, and, two, a spouse may just have second thoughts about 
reporting the incident, knowing the outcome of the report will put the officer/batterer in a definite position of being 
terminated from his or her job, upon the conviction for even a minor argument.<br>
<br>
It appears unlikely that any legislative changes will take place with this law in the near future.<br>
<br>
(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved, redistribution without permission is prohibited by law.</p>
