<head>
<title>NYC Sanitation Worker Killed by Illegal Haz-Mat</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p><font size=3>Excerpted from the ENN Daily Report - 11/15/96 - 11:55EST - Vol. 2, No.320 </font></p>
<p><font size=4><strong>NYC SANITATION WORKER KILLED BY HAZARDOUS MATERIAL</strong></font><br>
By Jim Fay, ENN NYC-NJ Bureau<br>
<br>
NEW YORK CITY (ENN) - NYPD Homicide detectives, assisted by Department of Environmental Protection agents 
and NYC Department of Sanitation Police, are investigating the death of a 23-year veteran NYC Sanitation worker, who 
was killed when he unknowingly handled a severely hazardous acid.<br>
<br>
On Tuesday, November 13, Sanitation worker Michael Hanly, 49, was on his route with his partner, Thomas Giammarino, 
when Hanly picked up an unmarked plastic bag that, on the surface, did not appear unusual. However, when Hanly tossed 
the bag into the truck hopper, it exploded from the crush. Unknown to Hanly and Giammarino was that, inside the bag, 
was a container marked with a skull and crossbones, containing Hydrofluric Acid. The explosion hit Hanly directly in his 
face and splattered on to Giammario.<br>
<br>
Across the street from the incident, which occurred at New Utrecht Avenue at 84th Street in Brooklyn, was the 
headquarters of the Bensonhurst Volunteer Ambulance Corps. Members of the ambulance corps tried to neutralize the 
sever burning of the acid on Hanly face by spray him with a garden hose. Hanly and Giammarino were rushed to New 
York Hospital Burn Unit in Manhattan, where he died from the inhalation of the fumes. Giammario remains in the hospital 
with facial and hand burns. Hanly's facial injuries were so severe that his wife was prevented from seeing him in the 
hospital.<br>
<br>
Hydrofloric acid is used in cleaning the fronts of buildings and etching in glass, and is highly caustic and toxic. Auto body 
shops also use hydrofloric acid in small quantities, and the Bensonhurst area of Brooklyn has many of these shops.<br>
<br>
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani responded to the hospital, and later at a press conference stated that the container was one gallon 
in size and the hydrofloric acid was 70 percent pure. Kings County (Brooklyn) District Attorney Charles J. Hynes stated 
that the perpetrators of this crime will be subject to murder and related charges for improperly disposing of toxic materials.</p>
<p>(C) Copyright by EmergencyNet News Service, 1996 -all rights reserved. Unauthorized redistribution prohibited by law.</p>
