<head>
<title>Rioting Breaks Out After Traffic Stop Shooting</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>ENN Special Report<br>
10/24/96 - 22:00CDT<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>Rioting Breaks Out After Traffic-Stop Shooting</strong></font><br>
By: Clark Staten, Analyst<br>
<br>
(ENN) In what is being described as &quot;major rioting,&quot; crowds in South St. Petersburg, Florida are reportedly setting fires, 
overturning cars, and throwing rocks tonight. The unrest reportedly started shortly after 17:30p.m. (5:30p.m.)EDT, when 
police shot a black motorist who had allegedly tried to run over an officer with his car. <br>
<br>
According to a police spokesperson, &quot;We have a major riot here...we've got a lot of police injured and many cars 
damaged.&quot; Police tell ENN that it started with localized unrest on only one or two blocks, but that it then quickly spread 
and may now involved sporadic looting and arsons over a large area.<br>
<br>
The Cable News Network (CNN) has reported, in the past few minutes, that several people have been injured, many of 
them police officers. Some firefighters may have been hurt as well; reportedly, they were attacked as they tried to fight a 
fire that may have been deliberately set. Several suspicious fires have been reported in the past hour in the affected area.<br>
<br>
At least one police car and a TV satellite truck from WTOG-TV were reportedly both torched and completely destroyed. 
A videographer was injured by flying glass in the melee. According to WTOG, the rioters then quickly turned to looting 
nearby businesses, as arson fires burned in others. <br>
<br>
An unidentified police spokesperson, at 21:45CDT told ENN that they had the situation &quot;contained,&quot; but that they had sent 
additional units to the scene to &quot;get the situation under control.&quot; St. Petersburg media sources say that the disturbance 
continues at this hour.<br>
<br>
ENN will continue to follow developments and provide additional details as they become available.<br>
<br>
(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved; contact ENN for redistribution rights.<br>
<br>
Emergency Response &amp; Research Institute<br>
6348 N. Milwaukee Ave., #312<br>
Chicago, IL. 60646<br>
