<head>
<title>Guatemala Soccer Stadium Disaster</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Emergencynet News<br>
10/16/96 - 22:35CDT<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>79 Killed, More than 150 Injured in Guatemala City Soccer Disaster</strong></font><br>
By: Clark Staten, Analyst<br>
<br>
(ENN) The first fifteen firefighters that responded to a reported collapse at a soccer stadium this evening in Guatemala 
City, Guatemala were immediately overwhelmed by the magnitude of the incident unfolding before them. Literally hundreds 
were found lying on stadium infield, or still in a tunnel leading into an already overpacked stadium.<br>
<br>
Victims were described as being &quot;blue or purple&quot; when found by rescuers, apparently suffering fromn a lack of oxygen and 
crushing injuries. Bystanders were seen giving Cardio-Pulmonary resuscitation (CPR) to several victims, in an attempt to 
save them. According to on-scene reports, at least 79 people have died and another 150 have been injured. Some are 
believed to have died of suffocation and others as the result of physical trauma. The death toll may rise.<br>
<br>
A local radio report is blaming the tragedy on an &quot;over-selling of tickets&quot; for the World Cup play-off match between 
Guatemala and Costa Rico, that was taking place at the Mateo Flores Stadium. Others said that fans without tickets may 
have &quot;rushed the stadium&quot;, in an attempt to gain entrance. According to government reports, the stadium may have 
contained 11,000 more than it's 45.000 capacity. Either way, something went terribly wrong and many paid the price by 
losing their lives.<br>
<br>
Guatemalan President Alvaro Arzu told fans and the press that he was &quot;deeply pained&quot; by the disaster and that he would 
suspend the game and was declaring a three day period of national mourning. Rescue operations there continued at the 
time of this report. Stadium officials promised that an investigation would be undertaken to ascertain the the cause of the 
tragedy.<br>
<br>
