<head>
<title>Westchester County Gets SWAT Equipment</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Excerpted from ENN Daily Report<br>
09/26/97 - 14:00EDT - Vol. 2, No. 270</p>
<p><font size=4><strong>WESTCHESTER COUNTY POLICE INCREASES POLICE HARDWARE </strong></font><br>
By Jim Fay NYC-NJ Metro Correspondent<br>
<br>
On March 21 of this year, a young police officer from the Westchester County town of Eastchester, just north of New 
York City, was killed, and two of his brother officers were pinned down and injured, by a sniper who held the team at bay 
for over one hour in the street. The time delay was primarily caused by the fact that the local and county police had to wait 
for the arrival of an NYPD heavy-duty armored vehicle to be dispatched a long way from Floyd Bennett Field in 
Brooklyn.<br>
<br>
Police insider in and around Westchester County talked openly about the fact that such equipment was not maintained by 
the County, whose demographics goes from extreme rich to some of the highest crime areas in NY state, outside of NYC. <br>
<br>
The County has reacted, and on September 24th, Westchester County Executive Andrew P. O'Rourke unveiled a new 
light armored vehicle to be used by the police in just the situations that occurred in Eastchester. O'Rourke also said that the 
unit, manufactured my General Motors, would also be used for natural disasters, such as snow storms and flooding, where 
traditional police vehicles would not work.<br>
<br>
The vehicle is 21 feet long, with a curb weight of over 12 tons. It can move at a land speed of 62 mph, with a &quot;swim 
speed&quot; of six miles per hour. The unit can carry one driver, one unit commander, and 8 others. It is equipped with eight 
periscopes and two night vision units.<br>
<br>
In addition to the armored truck, O'Rourke also announced several new police resources for Westchester County: a new 
helicopter, a mobile communications unit, a Special Response Team specializing in SWAT operations, a bomb robot and 
disposal unit, as well as a new police boat.<br>
<br>
The Eastchester incident (see ENN 02-082 part 1, March 22, 1996) took many police departments in Westchester by 
surprise. The bucolic town was caught off guard by the immediate need of highly trained and equipped officers to take 
command of the situation. It was reported to ENN at the time that the Yonkers Police Department Emergency Service 
Unit was training in Yonkers, not far from the Eastchester incident. But when the officers found out about the level of the 
incident, they were told not to respond because they &quot;weren't asked.&quot; Immediate command was taken over by the New 
Rochelle Police Commissioner, who is a retired NYPD Emergency Service Chief, who ordered the New Rochelle Police 
Emergency Unit to respond.</p>
<p>(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved; contact ENN for redistribution rights.</p>
<p><a href="/ennday.htm"><strong>Return to the ENN News page</strong></a></p>
</body>

