<head>
<title>NYC Hostage/Barricade; 2 Dead</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>EmergencyNet News Service<br>
9/17/96-- 07:39CDT - Vol. 2, No. 261<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>NYC Hostage/Barricade Situation Ends in Bloodbath</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
NEW YORK CITY (ENN) - A tense and dramatic standoff between New York City police and a gunman ended in a 
bloodbath in Brooklyn on Monday morning. The attacker killed his pregnant ex-girlfriend, wounded three people and then 
turned the gun on himself before an NYPD Emergency Services Unit tactical team stormed the apartment.<br>
<br>
The dead gunman was identified as James Parker, age 27. He held police to a standoff for about three hours. During that 
time, he sporadically fired shots inside of the second floor apartment, where he held ten people hostage. Parker was a 
fugitive with a long criminal record that dates back to 1988. In the past he had been arrested for: assault, illegal weapons, 
burglary and dealing in drugs. Parker was armed with a six-shot .38-caliber Titan revolver.<br>
<br>
Also killed was Parker's 17-year-old ex-girlfriend who was seven- months pregnant. She was shot twice in the head. 
Doctors at Kings County Hospital Center were unable to save the woman's fetus.<br>
<br>
Wounded in the incident was the 54 -year-old grandmother of the dead woman. She was reported to be in critical 
condition with a gunshot wound to the face. Another woman was shot in the leg and a 26-year-old man was shot in the 
chest. He was reported to be in serious condition. The other six hostages inside of the apartment, including three young 
children, did not suffer serious injuries.<br>
<br>
The situation began at about 0500 EDT, when Parker broke into the building located at 4305 10th Avenue in Brooklyn. 
Police were not notified that there was any trouble until about 0749 EDT. A woman called 911 to tell police of the hostage 
situation. When police arrived, they heard shots being fired. A short time later, a women threw a bloody T-shirt out of a 
window.<br>
<br>
At about 1000 EDT, more shots were heard. A woman at a window told police that two people had been wounded. A 
few minutes later, an irate Parker threatened to shoot all of the hostages unless police left. At another point, he threatened 
to shoot someone else if police negotiators called on the phone again.<br>
<br>
NYPD First Deputy Commissioner Tosano Simonetti said, &quot;At 10:05, we hear some more shots being fired. It's right after 
the third volley of shots from inside the apartment that we believe the young lady who is the girlfriend of Parker is 
screaming out, 'You must get in here because he's going to kill everybody. At that point, the on-sire commander made a 
decision to make an entry into the apartment.&quot;<br>
<br>
NYPD Chief of the Department Louis Anemone was the on-site commander. He was the one that gave officers the order 
to storm the apartment. Anemone said, &quot;Had we not made entry then, he probably would have shot more people. These 
are difficult decisions. Usually we wait. We've found in hostage situations that time pays. We were going to negotiate.&quot;<br>
<br>
At 1020 EDT, five percussion grenades were dropped from the roof into the apartment. A five-man ESU tactical team 
forced the front door of the apartment, which was barricaded with furniture. As police were breaking in, Parker shot his 
ex-girlfriend and then shot himself in the head.<br>
<br>
The following is an NYPD log of the incident that was furnished to ENN:<br>
<br>
-- 0501 to 0748 EDT: During this period, Parker sneaks into the apartment building and forces the first-floor occupants to 
the second-floor apartment at gunpoint.<br>
<br>
-- 0749 EDT: A woman makes a 911 call from the apartment, saying there is a man with a gun at 4305 10th Avenue. She 
names the suspect as James Parker. Police respond to the scene. A perimeter is established and phone communication is 
established with the occupants inside of the apartment.<br>
<br>
-- 0827 EDT: First shots fired from inside the apartment. A 26-year-old male, identified as Edward Hussey, is shot in the 
chest.<br>
<br>
-- 0831 EDT: Parker threatens to shoot all the hostages unless police leave.<br>
<br>
-- 0920 EDT: A woman throws a bloody T-shirt from a second-floor window.<br>
<br>
-- 0935 EDT: More shots are heard. Parker shoots a 20-year-old woman, identified as Lakissa Salansky, once in the left 
leg.<br>
<br>
-- 1005 EDT: More shots are fired. Parker shoots 54-year-old Barbara Hussey in the face.<br>
<br>
-- 10:20 EDT: Police officers storm the apartment.</p>
<p>(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved; Contact ENN for permission to redistribute.</p>
