<head>
<title>Preliminary Damage Assessments - Fran</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>Emergencynet News Service Daily Report<br>
9/6/96 09:46CDT<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>Initial Damage Reports - Hurricane Fran</strong></font><br>
By Paul Anderson, ENN Metro Correspondent<br>
<br>
WILMINGTON, NORTH CAROLINA (ENN) - Hurricane Fran was downgraded to a tropical storm/depression on 
Friday morning after it slammed into North Carolina, killing at least 11 people before it lost a great deal of its power. The 
storm dumped tons of rain after it came ashore near Cape Fear. It was said that between 10 and 15 inches of rain fell 
along the path of the storm. The worst rain may be yet to come because forecasters expect as much as 20 inches or more 
of rain will fall in the mountainous regions of West Virginia and Pennsylvania.<br>
<br>
At 0500 EDT, Fran was located about 25 miles north-northwest of Raleigh, North Carolina. The storm left widespread 
damage in its wake. When Fran came ashore on Thursday night, winds of up to 115 MPH were reported.<br>
<br>
At least 11 storm-related deaths were reported, almost all of them involved a vehicle of some kind.<br>
<br>
-- Near Conway, South Carolina, a 66-year-old woman was killed when her car hit some standing water and then crashed 
into a tree.<br>
<br>
-- A tree fell on a trailer home killing an 18-year-old female.<br>
<br>
-- In Durham, North Carolina, a volunteer firefighter was killed when a tree fell on his truck while responding to an 
emergency call.<br>
<br>
-- The other deaths were also traffic-related and two other people were killed when trees fell on their homes.<br>
<br>
The death toll was expected to rise after daybreak. Early reports of damage caused by the storm included a toppled 
church steeple and the loss of roofs off of two motels. Early helicopter surveys indicate that many homes and business have 
suffered wind and water damage, but that early evacuations may have saved many lives.<br>
<br>
Concerns are being raised in-land about the storm spawning tornados and the inevitability of heavy rain and flash floods, 
associated with the storm. Additional damage is possible as Tropical Depression Fran moves North and West. </p>
<p>(C) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996. All rights reserved; Contact ENN for republications rights.</p>
<p><a href="/ennday.htm"><strong>Return to the ENN News Page</strong></a><br>
</p>
