<head>
<title>1995, The Year of the Bomb</title>
</head>
<body>
<p>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service<BR>
Emergency Response &amp; Research Institute <BR>
6348 N. Milwaukee, Suite 312 , Chicago, IL 60646<BR>
<p>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE:1600CDT <BR>
Contact: Steve Macko, Managing Editor <BR>

<h2>1995, "The Year of the Bomb"</h2>
<p>

Chicago, IL., September 3, 1995 -- With this year only 3/4 over, one thing has become obvious to those that study terrorism and other such violent acts.  According to Clark Staten, Executive Director of the Chicago-based Emergency Response &amp; Research Institute, 1995 will go down in history as "The Year of the Bomb". Staten says that the reasons for this lethal escalation are myriad and multi-dimensional, and do not reflect only one specific theme. Although much of the violence has been attributed to different Islamic Extremist groups; they are not the only culprits in a seemingly worldwide pattern of deadly explosions.<br>
<p>

In defense of Staten's designation of "1995, The Year of the Bomb", he simply points to reports of the past few weeks as an example of what has occurring throughout the year:<p>

September 3, 1995 - A disaster was narrowly averted in a crowded outdoor Paris market on Sunday when a powerful bomb misfired, but nonetheless injured three shoppers. "If the bomb had gone off, it would have resulted in real carnage," said
Georges Sarre, Mayor of the 11th District of the French capital, where the incident took place in a market situated along Boulevard Richard Lenoir near the Bastille Square.<p>

 September 3, 1995- A second bomb within 24 hours exploded on the holiday island of Cyprus early on Sunday, with no immediate indication it was connected to one that nearly killed a nightclub owner the day before.  A package bomb, which 
according to media reports was thrown from a passing car, caused extensive damage to a furniture showroom and two other shops in the Nicosia suburb of Acropolis, police said. the motive is unknown at this time, but possibly related to crime gangs.<p>
<p>
 September 2, 1995- A truck bomb killed four people and wounded 83, the second such bombing in three days, when it blew up near an Algerian village bakery Saturday, the Algerian news agency APS said. The victims of Saturday's bomb attack in the village
of Meftah, 12 miles south of Algiers, included two girls aged nine and 19, the agency said. Several houses and shops were damaged by the blast. Local journalists said that the attack was apparently aimed at the village's police station.They said Meftah is a Moslem fundamentalist stronghold and considered as one of the most politically active places south of Algiers. The blast was the latest in a series of such attacks blamed on Islamic extremists, who oppose coming presidential elections.<p>
<p>
 August 31, 1995- A car bomb, allegedly planted by Moslem militants, ripped through a crowded working class district of Algiers Thursday, killing seven people and wounding at least 100, security sources said. Algerian President Liamine Zeroual, who rushed to the scene, blamed "terrorists," the government name for Moslem guerrillas, the official Algerian news agency APS said. Algerian radio, quoting security sources, said the 
bomb went off at 11.50 a.m. (6:50 a.m. EDT) in Mohamed Ounouri Square in the capital's Bab El-Oued district -- a densely populated area near the city center and a Moslem stronghold. The attack was believed to be the latest in a growing number of car bombs blamed by the authorities on Islamic fundamentalists.<p>
<p>
 August 30, 1995- Two potential bombers died when a device they were making blew up prematurely in a blast allegedly related to a spate of bombings in the Istanbul, Turkey this week, Anatolian news agency said on Wednesday. Two people died and 40 were wounded in five bomb explosions in Istanbul on Sunday and Monday. Four other bombs were defused. Turkish media have said the Islamist militant IBDA-C group and the previously unknown Kurdistan Islamic Union Party have taken responsibility for the 
bombings.<p>
<p>
August 27, 1995- French police are studying an unexploded bomb found alongside a high-speed rail line near Lyon, France on Sunday.   A train driver spotted the bomb, described as a "blue gas canister" by the track just north of Lyon, as he sped past 
on Saturday morning. The area was sealed off and experts defused the 25 kg (55 lb) explosive. Government officials say that they are drawing no immediate links to two recent guerrilla attacks in Paris.<p>
<p>
August 25, 1995- Texas police have arrested a man who was allegedly plotting to bomb the Travis County courthouse in Austin, Travis County Sheriff Terry Keel said.  Richard Perales, 36, was charged with possession of explosives after authorities, acting on a tip, found explosive devices, gunpowder and metal pipes in his home.  Perales was rrested Thursday as he boarded a bus in downtown Austin, near the courthouse. Keel aid he was wearing body armor when he was seized by police.  Perales reportedly "harbored ill will" toward the county that contains the Texas capital, possibly because of past legal problems that included several criminal charges and a failed lawsuit against the county government, Keel said.<p>
<p>
August 24, 1995- One policeman was slightly injured when a car bomb exploded outside a Helsinki, Finland police headquarters, authorities said Friday. The bomb xploded about 12:30 a.m. in a car in a parking lot outside the station, which is located in the city's Pasila area, according to police superintendent Stefan Gerkman. An officer ho was in the headquarters building at the time of the explosion was hit by glass fragments. The headquarters and buildings nearby were damaged. Police said they 
received no warning before the explosion. They also declined to comment on a possible motive for the bombing or on the investigation. No one claimed responsibility.
<p>

August 21, 1995- A suspected Islamic militant, possibly a woman, set off a anti-personnel bomb, Monday, that tore through two crowded commuter buses headed for Hebrew University in Jerusalem. The blast destroyed the bus, which disintegrated  into a smoking hulk of twisted metal and killed five people, including an American tourist.  The police investigation focused on two badly damaged and unidentified odies. Jerusalem Police Chief Arieh Amit said the condition of the woman's body suggested she could have been holding the TNT bomb. "I could see body parts everywhere," said Judy Shulewitz, a Cornell University student who was one of at least three Americans
wounded in the explosion. "There was blood all over the place."  The Muslim militant group Hamas claimed responsibility for the blast, which injured more than 100 other people.
<p>
 August 17, 1995- Two bombings in central Paris, within a month, have raised the issue of a new campaign of Moslem-inspired terrorism in France. A July 25th bomb attack at the Saint-Michel subway station, near Notre Dame Cathedral, killed seven people and 
wounded 84. On Aug. 17th a bombing on public square Charles de Gaulle-Etoile, near the Arc de Triumph, wounded 17 people, three of them seriously, and sprayed the area with nails, bolts, and shredded metal. Algerian Islamist fundamentalists from the Islamic Armed Group, or GIA, are suspected of the latest blasts. GIA has allegedly waged three years of guerrilla warfare in Algeria against a military-backed government, supported  by France. 
<p>
The attacks appear to be linked. Both bombs were made from gas canisters; both were planted at busy locations, near important historic/tourist attractions and were detonated during the evening rush hour. Police have sealed trash cans and other hiding places, across Paris, to prevent them from being used to hide devices. More than 1,500 armed security police have been assigned to patrol subway stations and important public places.<p>

The attacks are the worst such incidents since a wave of twelve (12) bombings in rance, in 1985-86, which claimed at least (13) lives and wounded more than three hundred.
<p>
 August 9, 1995- A bomb exploded just after midday on Wednesday in a Jeep parked in the east end of Montreal, Canada, killing the vehicle's driver and seriously injuring a 10-year-old boy who was standing on a nearby sidewalk. Police were reportedly 
investigating as to whether the bomb was related to a an on-going turf war between ival motorcycle gangs, which has resulted in several previous incidents. "It's certain hat with this kind of explosion we envisage the possibility of bikers, but it is too early to say," said Lieutenant-Detective Claude Lachapelle, of the Montreal Urban Community olice. Police said the bomb exploded at 12:45 p.m. (1645 GMT). The explosion threw 
the man out of the vehicle, tearing off one of his legs, police said.
<p>
 August 9, 1995- A car bomb exploded outside a district police headquarters in western Algiers on Tuesday slightly wounding three people, the official Algerian news agency PS reported on Wednesday.  The blast occurred on Tuesday at 7.40 p.m. (1840 GMT) near the district of Ben Aknoun, injuring three passers-by, APS quoted security officials as saying. The three were treated in hospital and discharged, APS said. The blast damaged four offices. 
<p>
On Sunday Aug. 6th, 11 people were killed and 25 wounded when a truck loaded with explosives blew up on the outskirts of Boufarik, some 30 km (18 miles) southwest of Algiers, according to an earlier official report. More than 40,000 people have 
allegedly been killed in Algeria since January 1992, when the authorities scrapped a general election that Islamist Fundamentalist were expected to win.
<p>
                        *****<p>
<p>
More troubling than the number and intensity of the attacks documented here is the fact that they are just a few of hundreds of bombings and thwarted bombing conspiracies that have occurred so far this year, throughout the world. Least we forget, there was also a still unsolved truck bombing in Oklahoma City that took more than 160 American lives and wounded more than 400.  
<p>
Staten said that even American street gangs have adopted terror tactics, and are using "molotov cocktails" or firebombs to intimidate potential witnesses or to exact revenge on rival gang members.  And, it is just not in the big cities. Within the past two weeks, ENN was notified of a series of streetgang firebomb attacks in Youngstown, OH.  previous reports of this type of incident have come from Chicago, New York, Los Angeles, Rochester, NY, and Miami, FL. Indictments in Chicago, earlier this year, also report that gang members have been attempting to buy commercial and military xplosives and even army Light Anti-Tank Weapons (LAW), to be used against law enforcement officers. The usage of military fragmentation grenades have been reported in several American jurisdictions. 
<p>
Staten concluded by saying that international fears of "the big one" (a nuclear detonation) may have decreased in recent years, but that it is far more likely than ever before that an individual could be injured or killed in one of dozens of "brush-fire" conflicts that are on-going in numerous regions, throughout the world. He predicted that the number of bombings and other attacks, motivated by geo-political, religious, 
racial, or ethnic causes will continue to increase in the foreseeable future.<p>
<p>
                              -30-<p>

(The following agencies/sources contributed to this report:<BR>
Reuters, UPI, AP, APS, CNN, BBC, CBC, CNBC, and several law enforcement/ government agencies)
<p>
