<body>
<h2>Flight 4184 Crash</h2>
		

<b>Plane Crash In Indiana; 68 Confirmed Deaths</b>
<P>



 (Updates details, gives death toll, confirms investigation) 
<P>

Chicago, IL, November 1, 1994  -- A commuter plane, American Eagle FLT.

4184, is confirmed down in a corn field near Roselawn/Lowell,

IN.  It dropped from O'Hare radar screens shortly after 16:00CST

this afternoon.  An eyewitness said that the plane disintegrated

upon impact.  Debris is reportedly strewn throughout a 3/4 mile

area . The flight is believed to be an American Airlines

commuter flight from Indianapolis to Chicago.  It is reported to

be a twin-engine AFR-72 Aerospatial that can carry up to

sixty-five (65) patients.  An initial report says that

sixty-four passengers and four crew members were on-board the

plane when it went down.
<P> 



Newton County Coroner Philpot responded to the scene and now

says that all aboard the plane have perished.  Rescue efforts

are said to have been halted by local officials after it was

confirmed that no survivors could be found at the scene. 

Earlier reports of multiple injuries turned out to erroneous, no

survivors have been found.  Local and state police reportedly

have encircled the area and secured it, until first light, when

a complete investigation will ensue. 
<P>



A FireNEWS/ENN correspondent, on the ground in Shuererville,IN.,

confirms that local ambulances and fire units have been recalled

from the scene and returned to service.  He said that there were

no survivors evident when the first rescue units arrived on the

scene. The crash is located in a rural area, and the remnants of

the plane are said to be located in the mud, 1/2 mile from the

nearest road.
<P>  



Fire departments and ambulances were said to have responded to

the accident from all over NW Indiana.  Mutual aid agreements

between numerous emergency agencies were activated, even though

it turned out that they were not needed. A psychological crisis

care intervention team has reportedly been requested for both

O'Hare airport in Chicago and to the airport in Indianapolis.
<P>



Although no cause has been determined for the crash, speculation

has centered on weather conditions in the Roselawn area.  Heavy

fog, wind, and rain were reported in the area of the crash, at

the time the plane went down.  No additional official details

will be available until a joint FAA/NTSB and State Police

investigation team is able to examine the scene and gather the

flight recorders and evaluate the information contained therein.

 That is expected to occur early Tuesday morning.
<P>

Additional information as it becomes available...
<P>



