<HEAD>
<TITLE>UsAir Ftl. 427 Crashes Near Pittsburgh</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 2130CDT
<BR>
Contact: Clark Staten,EMT-P
<P>
<HR>

<H2>USAir Flt. 427 Crashes Near Pittsburgh</H2>

Chicago, IL, September 9, 1994, (ENN)  2130CDT -- Reports from both emergency
service personnel and official sources indicate that a USAir
737-300 aircraft, enroute from Chicago to Pittsburg, has crashed
into a field Northwest of Pittsburg International.  The plane,
Flt. 427, was scheduled to arrive in Pittsburg at 7:09 p.m.
(local time).   Neither the FAA nor Pittsburg International
airport have reported any distress signal being recieved from
the striken aircraft.  Eyewitness reports from the scene
indicate that the plane banked and dove directly into the
ground, then burst into flames.  All 131 passengers and crew
have apparently perished in the crash.
<P>

Rescuers from Hopewell Township have described the scene as
"gruesome" with "body parts hanging from the trees".  The
largest piece of the plane, that is left intact, is believed to
be the tail and it is described as being a piece of slivered
metal about the size of a person.  Bits of baggage, shredded
parts of the plane, and severed limbs are reportedly strewn over
a large area.  Rescuers are believed to be hampered by darkness
and the rugged terrain in the area of the crash.
<P>

 Unconfirmed reports have suggested that the plane had exploded
prior to impacting the ground, which would account for the
debris being spread over a very wide area. Other eyewitnesses
have said that it "dove into the ground under full power". 
Contradictory reports continue to be received as additional
witnesses are interviewed.  The FAA has ordered the scene
sealed, and it is being surrounded by local and state police
officials. CBS News is reporting that the FBI has been called in
to the case because of the mysterious circumstances under which
the plane crashed. At least one unconfirmed report said that the
possibility of sabotage exists and that the explosion may have
been altitude detonated.
<P> 

According to an Allegeny County Spokesperson, no body recovery
will be attempted during nighttime hours.  An investigation and
extensive review of the crash site will reportedly be conducted
in the morning. It is to be supervised by the National
Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), the Federal Aviation
Administration (FAA), and local police experts. A local fire
department source said that both of the plane's "black boxes"
had been recovered and that they will be sent to Washington, DC
for evaluation.
<P>

Lisa Howard, from the Chicago Department of Aviation, is quoted
as saying that the Chicago Fire Dept. Critical Incident Stress
Debriefing (CISD) team has been placed on standby, should they
be needed to counsel the Chicago families of those lost, or to
travel to Pittsburg and assist with the large number of families
and rescuers that could suffer from the effects of grieving or
the devastating scene.  Experts in CISD say that circumstances
such as those involved in Pittsburg crash can cause severe
psychological or emotional distress, both now in a critical
sense and later as a delayed stress syndrome.
<P>

The investigation of this crash has just begun, and many more
technical and human details will need to be gathered before firm
conclusions can be reached.  The loss of "131 souls" will
undoubtedly be grievously felt by hundreds of family members and
friends. For now, more questions exist than answers.
<P>

(c) EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Emergency Response & Research Institute
<BR>
5656 N. Moody Ave., Chicago, IL 60646
