<html>

<head>
<title>Experts Say Bomb Most Likely Scenario; Flt. 800</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>EmergencyNet NEWS Service<br>
Friday, July 19, 1996<br>
Vol. 2 - 201<br>
<br>
<font size=5><strong>EXPERTS SAY BOMB IS MOST LIKELY 
SCENARIO FOR DOWNING OF TWA FLIGHT 800</strong></font><br>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor<br>
<br>
Private security and counterterrorism experts on Thursday were coming up with preliminary 
theories about what happened to TWA Flight 800 over Long Island on Wednesday night. Just 
about everyone was saying the same thing -- that it is still too early to determine exactly what 
happened. But still, based mainly on eyewitness reports, of seeing the plane going down in a 
fireball -- most experts believe that the most likely scenario was that a bomb was placed 
aboard the jumbo jet.<br>
<br>
James Donoghue, the editor-in-chief of Air Transport Magazine, said, &quot;It's got the hallmarks of 
a bombing, but it could be all kinds of other things. Of the number of 747s that have 
descended in flames, the vast majority have been because of bombs.&quot; Michael Barr, the 
director of aviation safety programs at the University of Southern California, said, &quot;Airplanes 
don't blow up just like that. I've been following 747s since 1970 and I've never seen one blow 
up like that.&quot;<br>
<br>
In New York City, Robert McGuire, the president of Kroll Associates and a former NYPD 
police commissioner, said that the crash was, in his estimation, suspicious. Mainly because the 
Boeing 747 has a historically good safety record. Mr. McGuire said that statistics suggest that 
it is highly unusual for a plane to just disintergrate all of a sudden. He said, &quot;The nature of the 
incident appears to be a traumatic explosion. There were no reports of a burning engine, 
smoke or the normal stuff that happens to these planes before an accident. Because there was 
no transmission back to the tower, there seems to have been immediate or overwhelming 
trauma.&quot;<br>
<br>
Kroll Associates is a highly regarded consulting and security firm. McGuire said that the 
destination of the plane, Paris, did not in itself suggest an unusual risk. However, its original 
departure point, Athens, Greece, has been on the U.S. government list of dangerous airports. 
Another security expert, Philip Stern, the managing director of the Fairfax Group, said that the 
original departure point of Athens was &quot;troublesome&quot; to him. Athens has long been known to 
act as a gateway to the Middle East. Stern said that Greece has a history of &quot;radical politicians 
sympathetic to Middle Eastern causes.&quot;<br>
<br>
But there is still a problem of how a bomb could be planted on the plane in Athens, fly all the 
way to New York, sit on the tarmac at John F. Kennedy International Airport for three hours 
and then suddenly blow up thirty minutes into a flight toward Paris.<br>
<br>
Mr. McGuire said that planting an explosive device aboard the plane would have been difficult 
to do in Greece, A bomb with an altitude detonator would have exploded when the plane was 
enroute to New York. But that problem may had been overcome if the terrorist were able to 
assemble the bomb in the plane's bathroom while traveling from Athens to New York and then 
just left the bomb on the plane.<br>
<br>
Another concern is the security at airports in the U.S. Former U.S. Department of 
Transportation Inspector General Mary Schiavo told ABC News that her last act before 
resigning last week was signing off on a new security assessment of U.S. airports. Schiavo 
would not reveal the results of this latest assessment, but she hinted that it probably was not 
good. She said that the assessment conducted before the last one was &quot;highly critcial&quot; of 
security.<br>
<br>
Schiavo said that her staff was able to penetrate airport security about 40 percent of the time. 
She said, &quot;My staff was able to, literally, get out on the tarmac, get on planes, get in cockpits 
and witness a number of test devices go through security. And we are troubled by that. We 
found that a lot of it was just plain lax attitude.&quot;<br>
<br>
According to Schiavo, there is new bomb detection equipment that has not been widely 
deployed in the U.S. because of cost. However, airports overseas are widely deploying the 
system. Schiavo said that to install the new bomb detection equipment would cost about $5 
billion. She, however, said, &quot;For some reason, the price tag that seemed so ridiculosuly 
expensive before the crash, after we have terrible tragedies like this, we come to our senses 
about such expenditures.&quot;<br>
<br>
How will investigators determine that it was indeed a bomb that caused Flight 800 to go 
down? Forensic experts will look for the residue of explosive that gather on debris. They will 
look for a twist in a chunk of the fuselage. They will also look for burns on the flesh of the 
victims and on cabin surfaces.<br>
<br>
No one single clue is likely to prove that it was a bomb. Instead, the investigators will almost 
have to reassemble all the collected pieces of the aircraft that have been recovered. Besides 
the plane itself, luggage, clothing, cockpit and cabin furnishings will also have to be pieced 
together.<br>
<br>
The most vital thing will be chemical analysis. When bombs explode, they essentially spray 
themselves all over the place. Bombs shoot debris through a plane and leave a distinctive 
pattern of small holes with metal edges splayed outward. Chemical residues and specific 
by-products of an explosion device can be identifed, including information about the types of 
explosives involved.<br>
<br>
Your editor has had occasion to examine the scene of an explosion in the past. While it was 
not essentially a criminal matter, one could very plainly see how the explosion happened. What 
direction the blast went and how powerful it was. Residue from the explosive could plainly be 
seen on the walls.<br>
<br>
If it was a bomb that brought TWA Flight 800 down, it may be a while before investigators 
make their final determination. In 1988, it took a full week before investigators determined that 
it was a bomb that brought Pan Am Flight 103 down over Lockerbie, Scotland. And that 
crime scene was on land and easier to investigate than the crime scene for Flight 800.<br>
<br>
The primary piece of evidence that allowed investigators to make their determination in the Pan 
Am case was a clue that was found in the samples of lining from the baggage compartment. 
The lining tested positive for plastic explosives. But Pan Am Flight 103 went down over land, 
TWA Flight 800 went down into the ocean. And because it went into the ocean it probably 
will make the investigators job more difficult. Certainly not impossible, but just more difficult.<br>
<br>
A case in point -- On 23 June 1985, the most deadly bombing in aviation history happened 
when an Air India 747 crashed off the coast of Ireland. 329 people were killed and the plane 
basically disappeared without a trace. For investigators, only circumstantial evidence allowed 
investigators to surmise that a bomb had gone off on the forward cargo hold.<br>
<br>
In Israel on Friday, the Haaretz newspaper reported that Israeli counterterrorism experts are 
looking for possible links between Moslem extremists and the crash of TWA Flight 800. The 
paper quoted an unidentified senior Israeli security source as saying that Israel was assisting 
U.S. intelligence agencies and the FBI in every way that it could. The newspaper said, &quot;Israel is 
checking whether there is any sort of connection between the explosion to Islamic terror 
organizations.&quot;<br>
<br>
Israeli officials have drawn any connection between the crash and the Arab-Israeli conflict. 
They say that they have not yet determined whether it was an accident or an attack. Israeli 
Brigadier-General Yigal Pressler, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's advisor on 
counterterrorism, said, &quot;We still don't know if this was an attack.&quot; Another Israeli security 
source, however, pointed to unspecified recent warnings of a possible attack on a plane and 
said, &quot;All the signs point to a bomb having been planted on the plane.&quot;<br>
<br>
One last note, the Federal Bureau of Investigation on Friday morning activated it Strategic 
Information Operations Center in Washington. This command center enable information on 
major cases to be assembled quickly for easy monitoring by top FBI officials. One FBI official 
said, &quot;We'd rather be ahead of the curve, than behind, if this turns out to be a terrorist 
incident.&quot;<br>
<br>
Just about every counterterrorism, security, and law enforcement expert that ENN has talked 
with and/or heard say that it probably was a bomb that brought down TWA Flight 800. But, in 
order to draw a firm conclusion, we all still have to wait for the scientific evidence to be 
brought forward and confim these suspicions.</p>
<p>(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.</p>
