<HEAD>
<TITLE>FBI Agent Killed in Drug Case</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from EmergencyNet NEWS Service-ENNFAX
<BR>
Saturday, March 23, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 083
<P>
<B>Philadelphia...</B>
<P>

<H2>FBI Agent Killed in Philadelphia Drug Case</H2>

An FBI agent was killed in a shootout while trying to buy drugs
from a reputed drug dealer.  The drug dealer was also killed.
Special Agent Charles L. Reed, age 45, a 16-year veteran of the
Bureau, and a suspect, identified as Jonathan Cramer, met in a
hotel parking lot and sat inside of a car.  Special Agent Reed 
was wearing a body microphone that taped the transaction on
Friday (03/22).

The suspect, Cramer, was heard on the tape, saying, "I don't
know if I can trust you.  I want to look in the suitcase and
see if you have a wire."
<P>

At news conference, a very upset FBI Director Louis J. Freeh
said, "They killed each other.  This was an extraordinary,
committed agent who never said no, who worked harder than
anyone in this division."
<P>

Reed was in the backseat of the car and Cramer was in the
front passenger seat.  Another person was in the driver's
seat.  Police would not elaborate on many portions of the
incident.
<P>  

Special Agent Reed was said to be shot several times and
the 24-year-old suspect was shot twice.  Once in the head
and once in the upper chest. Police said that no drugs were recovered and the transaction
was supposed to involve a negotiation over a kilogram of
cocaine.
<P>

Special Agent Reed was the 46th Special Agent of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation to die while in the line-of-duty in
the 87-year history of the Bureau.  He was also the first
Philadelphia-area agent to be killed in more than 30 years.
<P>
ENN sends its prayers and condolences to the family, friends, and co-workers of Agent Reed. Sadly, he is one of far too many officers to die while in the performance of their duties during 1996.
<P> 
