<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gang Crimes; Chicago's SW Side</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from ENNFAX: 01/30/96-14:00CST
<BR>
EmergencyNet News Service
<BR>
Vol. 2, No. 30
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>


<H2>STREET GANGS COME TO A QUIET CHICAGO NEIGHBORHOOD...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Managing Editor
<P>

Chicago's Clearing neighborhood is located on the far Southwest 
Side just west of Midway Airport in the 8th Police District.  For 
a very long time, it has been considered one of the better parts
of the nation's third largest city.  The area is heavily populated
by police officers, firefighters and other city workers.  Other
than the noise generated by planes at the airport, Clearing has
always been described as quiet.
<P>
But about 20 months ago, some residents of Clearing began to see
and hear signs of some type of change.  Gang graffiti started
showing up in alleys and on the walls of stores.  There was a rash
of residential burglaries.  Teenagers hanging out on West 63rd Street,
yelling at people in cars and flashing gang signs.  A boy was
beaten with a crowbar because he refused to join a gang. 
All signs of a change in the area.
<P>
Not unusual, many residents reportedly denied that there was any 
kind of a gang problem in their area.  They denied it up until early
December 1995 when two 13-year-old girls were shot and killed as
they sat in van outside of their school.  That shooting woke up
the residents of the community.
<P>
Street gangs can now show up any where.  From the poorest neighborhoods
to some of the better suburban towns.  Gang specialists estimate that
there are more than 50 street gangs operating in the Cook County
suburbs.  Communities such as Aurora, Elgin, Evanston, Schaumburg,
and Mount Prospect have gangs operating in their towns.
<P>
When most people think about street gangs, they picture black
and/or Hispanic youths.  But there white street gang members.
In fact, the first street gangs in Chicago were white.  Mostly
found in the Irish communities at the turn of the century.  And 
the white gangs battle for turf -- just as the double murder in 
Clearing in December indicates -- just like the black and Hispanic 
gangs.  The results from these turf battles can be just as deadly 
in Clearing as they are in the Logan Square area.
<P>
Irving Spergel is a sociologist at the University of Chicago.  He
has been studying street gangs for about 40 years.  Spergel said,
"All communities are at risk.  Gangs in some ways reflect the
tensions and pressures of people in the neighborhood.  The Southwest
Side is changing faster than the other sections of the city, with
new populations coming in.  Gangs don't move.  Families with gang
kids move."
<P>
That is why the Chicago street gang known as the Insane Popes is
starting to anchor itself in the Clearing area.  The criminal
activities of the Popes has grown as Latino gang members moved into
the area.
<P>
The main rivals of the Popes are the Two-Sixers, located mostly
in the 10th Police District and in the west suburban town of
Cicero.  The Two-Sixers are a mixed gang of Mexicans and whites and
are one the oldest, largest and most violent of the Hispanic
street gangs in Chicago.
<P>
Spergel said that gangs in white, middle-class neighborhoods may
organize and operate differently from gangs in poor, minority
areas.  However, it does seem that the same kinds of kids are
attracted to gangs for the same kinds of reasons, regardless of
skin color and economic background.  "They're all motivated by
the same things, although the level of crime varies with each
gang," Spergel said.  "These kids have a lot of personal problems.
The gang is a way they can take it out on society or on each other."
<P>
So, how can the parents of one of Chicago's finer neighborhoods
stop this encroaching problem?  The first thing they must do, and
experts agree that this is the hardest part, they must acknowledge
that there is a gang problem in their area to begin with and they
must find out if their children have any involvement with street
gangs.  A difficult, but necessary, task.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights reserved.
<P>
