<HEAD>
<TITLE>High School Violence; Gang Ties</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE-EMERGENCYNET NEWS SVC.-11/21/92-1100CST
<P>
<H2>SIXTEEN STUDENTS HURT, ONE DEAD, IN HIGH SCHOOL VIOLENCE</H2>
By: Paul Anderson, Metro Correspondent
<P>
Chicago, IL - Four high school students remain hospitalized
in fair to critical condition at area hospitals following two
separate incidents of gang-related violence that occurred
here yesterday.  Delondyn Lawson, age 15, was reportedly
killed by two shots from a .22 caliber semi-automatic
handgun.  Twelve other students were treated and released for
a variety of injuries.
<P>

The first incident involved a morning "pep rally" at Marshall
High School, 3250 W. Adams, on Chicago's West side.
Witnesses say that the troubles began as school security
officials and Chicago Police conducted metal detector
searches of students reporting to school.  According to a
police spokesman, at least eight (8) students were arrested
for weapons violations, disorderly conduct, and other
charges. Shortly there afterward, the students were to attend
a rally for the basketball team in the school gymnasium.
<P>

As the students gathered in the gym, a disturbance broke out
and students began to push and shove each other. During the
commotion, the pushing became violent and a section of the
brick wall surrounding the balcony collapsed.  Several
students fell from the balcony, and other were injured by
falling bricks and debris.  A total of thirteen (13) students
were transported by Chicago Fire Department paramedics to
several area hospitals. A fourteen (14) year old girl and a
seventeen (17) year old girl were admitted to University of
Illinois and Cook County Hospitals, respectively, for their
injuries.
<P>
<HR>
The second incident, involving a dispute over the proceeds of
a "dice game", took place at Tilden High School, 4747 S.
Union, at approximately 10:00 a.m..  The shooting took place
in a hallway during a class break.  According to witnesses
from the school, an argument began as one student asked
another for his share of gambling profits from a game that
had previously occurred. As the argument escalated, one of
the students reportedly punched Joe White, age 15, in the
mouth.  White responded by pulling a .22 caliber handgun and
opening fire. Deceased is Delondyn Lawson, age 15, who was
struck in the back.
<P>

Two other students were also wounded in the gunfire.  Wilson
Ching, age 17, and Barron Hall, age 15, were transported to
Cook County Hospital were they were considered in critical
condition.  A third youth, reportedly an accomplice of the
gunman, was struck by a car while they were attempting to
flee the scene of the shooting, and was taken to St.
Bernard's hospital in good condition. The assailant, Joe
White, was arrested a short time later when found hiding
under the porch of a nearby building.
<P>
<HR>
Friday's incidents follow weeks of violence and mayhem in the
Chicago school system.  On November 13, 1992, thirty (30)
students were arrested as the result of an alleged gang-
fight at Farragut High school on Chicago's near Southwest
side.  Reportedly, as many as fifty (50) Chicago police
officers were called to the school shortly after 10:30 a.m.
in an attempt to quell a "running battle" that began in the
school's lunch room and spread to nearby hallways and onto
the sidewalk.
<P>

According to police records, twenty-nine (29) students were
charged with mob action in this incident and one was charged
with battery to a school security guard. Six (6) students
were injured in the melee and transported to St. Anthony's
Hospital, where they were treated for contusions and minor
lacerations and released. According to Farragut principal
Steve Newton, the major disturbance was the result of an gang
confrontation that had occurred the day before.  Allegedly,
the earlier fight resulted in retaliation and the major
disorder of the 13th.
<P>
<HR>

November 10, 1992 was also a tragic day for the Chicago
public schools.  As classmates watched, 13 year old Willie
Clayborn of the Sherman Elementary School turned a .22 cal.
handgun on himself and pulled the trigger. Willie was
pronounced dead shortly thereafter at an area hospital.
Classmates described Clayborn as "playing with the gun", when
it went off and struck him in the head. 
<P> 

Reportedly, the youth had earlier shown the gun to several other students and
had pointed it at his own stomach without incident, then he
pointed it at his head and it went off. Clayborn's parents
denied any knowledge of his having a gun and his mother even
said that she had prohibited him from having "toy guns".
Nonetheless, he had one on November 10th, and it took his
life.
<P>
<HR>
According to a recent survey by "Who's Who Among American
High School Students", these incidents are not isolated
occurances.  The survey, which interviewed high school aged
youths from all over the country, said that 40% of the
respondants reported that they knew of violent incidents that
had occurred in their schools.  A third of the reported
incidents were believed to be racially or gang motivated.
More surprisingly, over a third of the male students surveyed
said that they personally own or have access to handguns.
Almost half of the male students interviewed said that they
knew of someone who had brought a weapon to school.
<P>

Clark Staten, Executive Director of the Emergency Response &
Research Institute - a Chicago-based emergency services think
tank, said that the problem is far reaching and appears to be
rapidly escalating.  "Reports are being received from urban
areas, suburban, and rural schools", Staten said.  "Most
notable are the numerous incidents in the New York City
Schools, where dozens of children have been killed this
year...and in the Los Angeles County schools, where gang
confrontations seem to occur on almost a daily basis", the
veteran emergency manager added.  "Now, we see this same
wanton violence erupting in the Chicago School system", he
continued.
<P>

Staten, who operates a country-wide computer based
information sharing system for emergency responders and
managers, said that the preliminary statistics for youth
crime seem to be rising at a disproportionate rate to the
overall increase in street crime. "It seems more and younger
people are involved in violent crime, and that they are
engaging in acts that we may have not seen a few years ago",
Staten said. 
<P> 

"Street gang leaders are reportedly using
younger members to carry guns and drugs for them, because
they know that if the juveniles are caught...they will
receive better treatment and more lenient sentences than
older gang members", the experienced emergency analyst added.
"This earlier and more extensive involvement by younger gang
members seems to be leading them to more violent behavior at
an earlier age", Staten concluded.
<P>

