<TITLE>Terrorist Threat Increases</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
Emergencynet NEWS Service
<BR>
Emergency Response & Research Institute
<BR>
<HR>
6348 N. Milwaukee, Suite #312 , Chicago, IL 60646
<BR>

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 23:00CDT
<BR>
Contact: Paul Anderson, Metro 
<BR>
Phone:	 (312) 631-ERRI (3774)
<BR>
FAX:	 (312) 631-4703
<BR>
Internet: enn@emergency.com
<BR>
<P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H2>Security Tightens; Terrorist Threat Increases</H2>
<P>
Chicago, IL, (ENN) October 2, 1995--Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman and nine
of his convicted co-conspirators were led from a courtroom in
handcuffs today.  They had been convicted of a variety of
charges, most of them relating to a number of conspiracies to
conduct a war of "Urban Terrorism" against America. Among their
alleged targets were the United Nations, the NYC FBI Headquarters,
the Lincoln and Holland Tunnels, and a number of world leaders.
Their murderous intent alleged to have been to create fear and
change the Mid-East policy of the United States. Their methods
included guns and bombs and fiery rhetoric, designed to cause
discontent and revolution among Moslems in America.
<P>
Concurrent with the verdict in the Rahman trial, U.S. Secretary
of Transportation Federico Pena announced that he had ordered
security at all U.S. airports stepped up to levels unseen since
the Persian Gulf War.  An purposefully anonymous Transportation
Department analyst is quoted by the Associated Press as saying
that increased security wasn't as the direct result of specific
threats against aviation targets, but rather, indicative of an
increase in the overall threat level against the United States.
<P>
Clark Staten, Executive Director and analyst for the
Chicago-based Emergency Response & Research Institute (ERRI),
said that the current threat level is "multi-dimensional" and
"multi-faceted".  By that, Staten said that he means that the
current threats against the U.S. are now coming from a variety
of groups and for a variety of reasons.  In particular, Staten
said that priority should be given to concerns about:
<P>

 
<UL>
<LI>The visit of Pope John Paul this week. The Pope was previously
  targeted by Moslem extremists during a visit to the
  Philippines
<LI>Revenge, by Egyptian extremists, for the conviction and       
  imprisonment of Rahman and his followers
<LI> U.S. participation in and support for another Mid-East peace  
  accord between Israel and the PLO
<LI> Detention of and possible extradition of alleged Hamas
  financier Mousa Abu Marzook
<LI>Already issued public threats made by Hamas, Islamic          
  Jihad, Hezbollah, The Popular Front for the Liberation of
  Palestine (PFLP), and others
<LI>The possibility of a terrorist act against the 50th
  Anniversary celebration of the founding of the United
  Nations, to be held later this month in New York City.
</UL>
<BR> 
<P> 
Staten said that ERRI's computer assessment of the current
threat situation is as great as it has been in recent years,
largely due to a combination of factors surrounding multiple
targets, multiple motivations, and multiple potential
antagonists. He said that increased airport security measures
are totally warranted at this time and that additional measures
may need to be taken if additional threat intelligence is
developed in coming days.
<P> 
Aside from air traffic, Staten said that the following list of
potential targets could also be included in future security
considerations:
<P>
<HR>
<BR>
<H5>Possible Targets of Opportunity</H5>
<BR>
<UL>
<LI>1. Unknown briefcases, packages, boxes, etc., left unattended in
areas of public transportation or business (i.e. Airports,
Train Stations, Bus Stations, Court Houses, Banks, Stock
Exchanges)
<LI>2. Sports stadiums, political gatherings, large shopping malls,
public parks (i.e. any place that people congregate in density)
<LI>3. Seemingly abandoned cars, parked in an areas that are densely
inhabited, or in close proximity to other "high-risk" targets.
(i.e. Near any of the above mentioned areas, embassies, 
government installations)
<LI>4.  Civic, Government, Religious, Ethnic, other recognized
leaders... may be the targets of assassination attempts.
<LI>5. Electrical Power plants, Natural Gas facilities, Nuclear
Plants, Chemical factories, telephone exchanges or central
offices, or any other public utilities that could cause
disruption of service or a danger to the public.
<LI>6. Anything that could be destroyed and undermine the public
confidence in government or civic institutions. (Computer
networks,   TV/Radio channels, traffic control systems, sewers,
water supplies)
<LI>7. Emergency Response facilities; Fire/Police/EMS stations,
FBI/Secret Service/ATF/DEA/CIA or other federal law enforcement
offices or facilities. All in all...any government building.
</UL>
<P>
<BR>
Staten said that all of the above have been chosen as targets,
in a number of other countries where extremists have operated in
the past. Further, he said that terrorist tactics used in Egypt,
Japan, Lebanon, Israel, and elsewhere could potentially be
imported to the United States and used with devastating
effectiveness.
<P> 
<HR>
<P>
