<TITLE>EMS Haz-Mat Scenario</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>
**EXCLUSIVE-EMERGENCY MEDICAL SERVICES MAGAZINE-02/01/92**
<BR>
<H3>A BAD DAY "ON THE JOB"</H3>

By Clark Staten, EMT-P, I/C
<BR>

The shift had began just like any other day. You and your
partner had done all of the routine tasks that make up the
hours of sheer boredom that can occur in between the moments
of excitement that make up life of an EMT. As you are
completing the maintenance and inventory of your equipment,
the klaxton sounds and the speaker cracks;
<P>

"Medic 3...Medic 3...a man down in the factory at Ash Lane
and 3rd Street... a man down...Ash Lane and 3rd Street." "Got
that Medic 3", the dispatcher asks.
<P>

The station Captain grabs the microphone and says, "Medic 3
to a man down at Ash and 3rd...KXZ4413...station clear at
0914 hrs."  He turns and hands you a slip of paper with the
address.
<P>

You and your partner Anne head for the ambulance. As she
starts the engine, you begin to write the preliminary
information on the run report.  The radio crackles as you
pull onto the street adjacent to the station;
<P>

"Medic 3...Medic 3... a second report of a man down in the
factory at 3rd and Ash...that's a second victim...Medic 3".
You grab the microphone and acknowledge the transmission,
"Medic 3 got it...a second victim in the factory". You hang
the microphone back in it's socket.
<P>

Anne hits the "whoop" setting for the siren as you approach a
very busy intersection.  A large black Cadillac sedan blocks
your path by stopping immediately in front of you. Anne hits
the airhorn also, with little response from the vehicle's
occupants.  The elderly man in the Cadillac doesn't
acknowledge your movement until you pull along side him and
give him a sidesways glance. You continue with your response,
not giving it another thought... that happens everyday.
<P>

As you continue down the tree-lined avenue, you here the fire
radio frequency crackle to life; "Engine 10...Engine
10...respond to an EMS incident in the factory at 3rd and
Ash...that's a man down Engine 10...you are following Medic
3...got it..Engine 10?
<P>

"Engine 10's got it...dispatch...following Medic 3 to 3rd and
Ash for a man down".
<P>

"Gee...we even got help", Anne says matter of factly as she
guided the ambulance onto 3rd Street.  Normally, an EMT
engine or truck company was dispatched if the ambulance had a
long response time, or there was a possibility of multiple
victims. It looked like the report of the second man down had
prompted dispatch to send an additional unit.
<P>

Anne says; "Hey Mark, what do think we got on this one"?
"What do you think they make in that factory?", she
continued.  "Come on...Mark...you are in charge of this
thing...you are supposed to know this stuff", Anne laughs.
<P>

You grin at the good natured ribbing, think for a couple of
seconds, and say; "I don't know...did they say what was in
the factory?"
<P>

"Naw...they just said `a man down'...you know how that
goes...they never seem to be able to get enough information",
Anne replied.
<P>

"Well, we'll treat it like a cardiac until proven
otherwise...OK?", you answer.
<P>

Anne again hits the "yelp" setting for the siren as you pass
through a busy intersection about six blocks from the
incident scene.  She turns the siren off as you enter the
driveway into the factory parking lot. There appear to be
several people in the lot, most of them surrounding a door at
the side of the factory.
<P>

As you and your partner pull up adjacent to the crowd and you
roll down the window, a worker is shouting; "Hey you
guys...hurry up he's out cold...come on...hurry up!".  You
notice a man, covered with a blanket, lying on the ground
near the door.  Another worker screams; "He's not
breathing..he's not breathing...come on...hurry up!".
<P>

You exit the vehicle and open the side door of the ambulance.
Your partner has come around from the driver's side and helps
you to grab the drug box and cardio-gram monitor.  As a
secondary thought, you also grab an extra oxygen tank with
regulator and move towards the striken man.
<P>

Just as you arrive at his side, a man grabs your arm and
says; "My name's Paul Anderson...I'm a supervisor here...we
have another man down inside the plant...can you help?"?  You
look at the man near you and realize that somebody has rolled
a blanket and placed it under his neck as if it were a
pillow. You immediately remove it and hyperextend the man's
neck. You see his chest gasp, and he begins breathing.
<P>

That accomplished, you answer the supervisor and direct your
partner at the same time; "Ok...no problem...Anne, go with
the man and see what else we have...I'll go ahead and check
this guy out".  Anne grabs the "jump kit" and follows the
supervisor into the plant. You then begin to attempt to get a
history from the other assembled workers.
<P>

"Hey... any of you guys see what happened to him"?  "Anybody
know what happened", you ask the other men.  One of them is
coughing and says; "He was working with a truck driver on
filling one of the film processing vats and I think they
mixed up the hoses".
<P>

The man continued to cough and continues; "You guys got any
oxygen?....I'm a little short of breath myself". You reach to
grab the oxygen tank with mask attached, turn it on, and hand
the mask to the man who has been talking to you. "Here...try
this and have a seat...see if you feel better in a minute",
you advise the man.  Your mind begins to churn and you you
begin to realize that this incident may have grown larger
than you had anticipated.
<P>

You take the microphone from your epaulet and contact the
dispatch center; "Medic 3 to Dispatch...Medic 3 to
dispatch...we have another victim...give me a second medic
unit and a supervisor...trouble breathing...got that
dispatch?".  The dispatcher acknowledges your transmission
and asks; "Medic 3...can you give me an update as to what you
have there...Medic 3...an update for the alarm center?".
<P>

"Medic 3 to Dispatch...give me a couple of minutes..can you
give me an ETA on Engine 10?...they are responding?...right
dispatch?", you ask.  You then hear the dispatcher ask the
Engine Company it's estimated time of arrival on a speaker in
the nearby ambulance.  Events seem to be speeding up, and it
now seems important to get some additional help at the scene.
The engine company officer tells the dispatch center that
it's ETA is about three minutes, and that they had been
responding from the other side of their still alarm district.
<P>

"Medic 3...you have a engine company in three minutes, a
second ambulance, and an EMS supervisor responding...anything
else Medic 3?", the dispatcher answers. You respond; "Message
received...Dispatch...it looks like we have a total of three
victims at this time...I'll give you more when I have it".
<P>

As you hang your microphone back onto your epaulet, you
insert an oral airway into the unconscious worker, and note
that he is still breathing, with shorter inhalations than
expirations.  He accepts the airway without difficulty and
his breathing seems to improve.As you lean closer to him to
insert the airway, you notice a peculiar smell coming from
his clothing, but are unable to identify it.
<P>

A small internal voice breaks through your attention to the
man lying in front of you; it begins to whisper to your
consciousness, "There is something...wrong...terribly wrong
here...you better get some more help".  You dismiss the
rising sense of anxiety and return to concentrating on the
task at hand.  Just as you are applying an oxygen mask to the
man you are treating, a man stumbles out of the door where
the supervisor and your partner had entered.
<P>

He appears excited and out of breath. He shouts to you
in a slightly incoherent manner; "Hey...fireman...you better
get in there...your partner and Mr. Anderson are sick!". the
man slumps to the ground and is gasping for air. You begin to
hear the sound of an approaching siren, but disregard it, due
to the fact that the man said... your partner is down!  Your
little voice begins to scream at you, "You have to help
her...you have to get to your partner... you're responsible
for her".  You grab the oxygen tank and mask from the
astonished man who has been using it and start into the
building.
<P>

As an afterthought, you turn to the group of men that is
getting larger and shout to them; "There will be some firemen
here in a minute...you guys tell them where I went...I'm
going to help the people in the building".  Everything now
seemed to be moving so fast that it was turning into a blur.
<P>

You grab the microphone as you move rapidly down the aisle of
the factory; "Medic 3 to Dispatch...Medic 3 to Dispatch
...EMERGENCY!... give me an EMS Disaster Plan...
EMERGENCY!...give me a plan!...my partner is reported down...
a medic down...got it dispatch??".
<P>

The seemingly dispassionate voice responds to your frantic
plea; "Message Received...Medic 3...you are requesting an EMS
Plan...you have one Engine company on the scene, a supervisor
enroute, and we will fill the assignment with three more
ambulances and a Chief", the dispatcher answers.  You
continue to move down the aisle, now moving more rapidly,
glancing to the right and left and searching for your partner
and the striken supervisor.
<P>

You hear a muffled voice on your portable radio, and it
sounds like your partner.  The voice is unintelligible, but,
you hear the word "help!".  The odor that you noticed before
is becoming stronger but, you still can't recognize it.  It
does, however, somehow remind you of the smell of those
sliced nuts that your mother used to put on green beans.  You
disregard the distraction... you have to find your partner.
You begin to feel a little dizzy, and your throat feels dry,
but you attribute it to the excitement of the moment.
<P>

As you turn the corner at the end of the aisle, you hear the
Engine 10 officer on the fire frequency. The voice echos
through the relatively quiet factory; "Engine 10 to
Dispatch...we are on the scene...we have multiple victims and
what appears to be as hazardous materials incident...give me
a full Haz-Mat Response and a second alarm...got it
dispatch?".  You realize that the officer must be right, but
it is getting harder to think and you have to find your
partner.
<P>

Your vision is dimming, and you begin to feel nauseated as
you finally see three people lying near a large tank. One of
them is the seemingly lifeless form of your partner. Just as
you reach them and start to bend over to begin your
assessment of your partner, another wave of nausea washes
over you... and things go black.
<P>
<BR>

                   *******************
<BR>
<P>

A manager of the plant has met the engine company as it
arrives in the parking lot.  He had exited the building from
another exit and had walked around the block to the area
where the emergency vehicles were gathering. A second
ambulance arrived on the scene almost simultaneous with the
firefighters from Engine 10.  The manager advised the Captain
of Engine company that this is a film processing plant that
extracts silver from used X-Ray plates.  He also indicated
that the process can cause a production of Hydrogen Cyanide
gas.
<P>

The Captain asks several more questions of the manager and
bystanders. One of them volunteered; "The ambulance driver
went in the building...they said something about his partner
being sick, and he grabbed the oxygen mask from that
guy...(pointing at a nearby worker, who looked ashen and was
coughing)...then he ran in the building".
<P>

The Captain directed a firefighter to begin giving oxygen to
the man and shouted to the medics, who were getting their
equipment out of the vehicle; "You guys set up a triage area,
I'm going to send a team into the building to see how many
more victims we have!".  One of the Medics waved his hand in
acknowledgement and set about removing the clothing of the
man he had found on the ground.
<P>

Captain Hall slipped his microphone from the pocket of his
"turn-out" gear and entoned; "All units at the Extra alarm...
we have a report of Hydrogen Cyanide gas involved in this
incident...we are setting up the decontamination  and triage
area in the parking lot located to the north of the
building...bring all victims to this location...do not
acknowledge this transmission". "Engine 10 to Dispatch...did
you hear that transmission?", he continued.
<P>

"We got it Engine 10...you have a full Haz-Mat Response, a
second alarm, an EMS plan, and the Duty Chief has been
notified and is responding...need anything else Engine 10?".
"Negative..Dispatch...not at this time", the Captain
answered.  Captain Hall quickly turned to a truck company
that was pulling up on the scene and directed the Lieutenant
to "suit-up" in protective clothing and Self-Contained-
Breathing-Apparatus, and enter the building for rescue
purposes.  "We got people down in there...Lou...tell your
people to get the lead out!", the Captain ordered.
<P>

Chief Burns, who was on call, was arriving on the scene as
the Capt. Hall directed Engine 9 to set-up a hose line to be
used in the decontamination area. The Hazardous Materials
Unit arrived shortly thereafterward and began the process of
verifying the identification of the substance involved and
began working with the paramedics to develop a treatment plan
for the victims.  The firefighters began to wash the victims
that were already outside the building, as they continued to
receive oxygen by mask.
<P>

Firefighter Haskell activated the on-board computer in the
Hazardous Materials Van and quickly accessed a database on
medical care for the patients.  The EMS supervisor, Steve
Sweet, had arrived and was consulting with the Hazardous
Materials team and Chief Burns as the first medic was brought
from the door of the building. It was Anne Richards...and
with bad news...she wasn't breathing.
<P>

From the database, the medics quickly verified the
administration of amyl nitrate capsules with oxygen.  A
Medic, in complete "turn-out", broke an ampule, taped it
inside the positive pressure oxygen mask and placed it on
Anne's face. Simultaneously, another firefighter was removing
the striken medic's clothing and washing her with a downsized
hose that was connected to an 1 1/2" hose line".  As she was
washed down, another firefighter was wrapping her in a
blanket.  The same process was being performed on Mark and
the factory supervisor.
<P>

In the triage area, one medic was preparing intubation
equipment, while another was working on the preparation of
boluses of sodium thiosulfate (50cc -25% solution) and sodium
nitrate (10cc of 3% solution). As each of the victims were
grossly decontaminated, they were moved into the triage area.
Amyl Nitrate ampules were continually administered, along
with high-flow oxygen. The I.V. Drugs were given, as soon as
access to a clean vein was provided. The patients were
intubated.  Steve Sweet was on the radio with the appropriate
Trauma Center to receive additional information and
coordinate the movement of victims to area hospitals. The
rescue continued with decontamination, triage, treatment, and
transport to an appropriate hospital.
<P>
<BR>

                     ******************
<BR>
<P>

Fortunately, Mark and Anne both lived, although both were
hospitalized in critical condition for many days.  Anne is
now recieving a disability pension and Mark must make
periodic visits to a pulmonary specialist. The factory
supervisor was not so lucky; he had a previous heart
condition and although successfully resuscitated from the
cyanide poisoning, died later from congestive heart failure.
Three other workers were admitted to the hospital and
survived.
<P>

The effectiveness of the rest of the system's response to
the medic's lack of recognition was what made the difference.
Once the problem was recognized, and sufficiant and correct
resources were called to the scene, the incident was
adequately managed. The disaster involved a sense of "tunnel
vision" and "denial" on the part of the paramedics. After
all, they had reasoned, it had never happened before.  But,
as this story demonstrates...it could happen to you!
<P>

Please...Be careful out there!
<P>
                         -30-

