<HEAD>
<TITLE>Feds Take-On Streetgang</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from: ENNFAX, Vol. 2, No. 54, 02/23/96
<BR>
EmergencyNet News Service
<P>

<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>

<H2>FEDS TARGET CHICAGO STREET GANG...</H2>
By Steve Macko
<P>

Federal law enforcement authorities and prosecutors have set 
their sights on ending the 25 year reign of perhaps the largest
criminal street gang in the United States ... The Gangster
Disciples.
<P>

For more than six years the feds have been collecting evidence
and building their case against the gang that has as many as
30,000 members in 35 states.  When a person thinks about a
street gang such as the Gangster Disciples images of drugs,
murder and money laundering cross the mind.  But that does not
even begin to suggest the reach of this criminal enterprise.
<P>

The leaders of the gang reach from behind prison walls of some
of the toughest prisons and still maintain control of what is  
happening on Chicago streets.  Street gang expert and Chicago 
State University professor George Knox said, "They're one of
the most successful, illegal home-grown corporations in the
modern American underground economy.  They're trying to make a
fortune through crime."
<P>

Professor Knox estimates that the Disciples make more than
$100 million a year in narcotic drug sales, mostly cocaine.
Knox also said that the gang has a lengthy constitution, uses
codes for passing messages from one another, and has a typical 
gang emblem.  The Gangster Disciples even have a pledge of
alligiance, membership applications and members must pay dues.
About applicants who wish to join the gang, Knox added, "You 
will be investigated just like you would be at a bank if you
wanted to take out a mortgage."
<P>

This insidious street gang runs itself like a Fortune 500
company.  It's chairman and one of its board of directors 
currently sit in prison.  On the streets there are governors
and regents running the day-to-day operations.  It's this
high level of organization that sets the Gangster Disciples
aside from the usual loose band of thugs that make up most
street gangs. Police in Chicago say that there has been no criminal organization,
including the infamous "Mob," that has been so conspicuous in
the City since Al Capone during Prohibition -- and even Capone
pales in comparison.
<P>

Chicago Police Commander Donald Hilbring heads the gang crimes
investigations unit.  Hilbring said, "We're not only talking about
running drugs.  We're talking about running as many businesses as
they can.  We're talking about politics.  They want to control the
entire community.  It's the same thing as Capone."
<P>

The leader of the Gangster Disciples is 45-year-old Larry Hoover,
who has been in prison serving a sentence for murder for more than
20 years.  Even though he has been in prison for about half his
life, he still reportedly is able to keep total control of this
gang.  It is said that besides maintaining control over thousands of
members in the streets -- he also allegedly has control of some 5,400 inmates in
state prisons.  How is this possible?
<P>

Evidence uncovered by a federal criminal investigation has found
out that Hoover's incarceration has apparently enabled him "to
consolidate power and develop unquestioning allegiance among the
members of his gang."  According to prosecutors, the Gangster Disciples are even better
organized in prison than they are on the streets.  Before anyone
becomes a member of the gang they are screened and their "street" references
are checked.
<P>

In recent years, Hoover has allegedly been trying to do a "con job" and has said
that his gang has undergone a conversion.  The gang is now involved
in community activism and not crime, Hoover is quoted as saying. In answer to that, 
Jack Hynes, the Cook County prosecutor who is in charge of gangs prosecutions, said, "Hogwash!"
<P>

After the gang cornered a large chunk of the illegal drug trade in
Chicago they have reportedly branched out to other states.  Their heaviest activity
is in the Midwest states of Minnesota, Missouri and Wisconsin.
<P>

According to Prosecutor Hynes, 43 percent of 650 gang-related
murders in Chicago between 1990 and 1994 involved the Gangster Disciples in one
way or another. Authorities say that in recent months it appears that the gang has
been attempting to lower its profile, but illegal activity continues.
In January, a high-ranking member was murdered in his West Side bar.
More than 1,000 people attended the wake. 
<P> 

Jack Hynes said, "We still see the violence.  They're trying to make
money.  But they're in a holding pattern.  This has definitely
crimped their style.  We've got them off their guard, but it can't
stop here.  This is only Round One."
<P>

The investigations continue and a series of trials is now underway.
Once the federal government is able to convict Hoover and his
co-horts it is hoped that they can transfer this powerful criminal
to a federal prison and then severely limit his contact with the
outside world.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
<P>
<A HREF="/polcpage.htm"><B>Return to the ENN News Page</B></A>

</BODY>
</HTML>

