<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gangs Invade "Down Under"; New Zealand</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Friday, May 31, 1996 
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 152
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>
<H2>STREET GANGS COME TO THE SOUTH PACIFIC ...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor
<P>

Have you ever heard or come into the contact with any of the following street gangs?  The Devil's Henchmen?  Satan's Slaves? The Headhunters?  The Grim Reapers?  No, you won't find any of these gangbangers on the streets of Los Angeles or Newark or Chicago or New York or even in Omaha -- you'll find them in the cities of -- of all places -- New Zealand.
<P>

Gangs are reported to be on the rise in one of the most unusual and remote places in the world.  Their gang names and insignias seem to be patterned after their American counterparts.  They even conduct drive-by shootings -- just like you'll find on the streets of Los Angeles.
<P>

One politician told the New Zealand parliament, "These are not packs of hooligans who occasionally rough up a pub and occasionally pillage a small town.  This is organized crime.  It strikes at the very heart of civilized society."
<P>

Police in New Zealand, a country with a population of about three million people and located southeast of Australia, say that there are 70 major gangs in the country with about 4,000 hard-core gang members.  If you include associates and prospective wanna-be members, that number grows to about 11,000.
<P>

A police officer, who works in an intelligence unit, said, "We're not talking about guys playing with their bikes anymore.  We're talking about the need to control territory ... because it's the control of money."
<P>

There is great concern amongst New Zealand law enforcement officials about the New Zealand gangs forming links with Asian triads.  The police intelligence officer said, "The hold that these guys are getting is becoming more serious.  It's becoming a bigger, more international thing." In April, police said that an Asian triad tried to hire a New Zealand gang to kill a police detective because he was investigating illegal drug shipments from Hong Kong.
<P>

New Zealand police have classified their gangs into three groups.  They are: ethnic gangs, motorcycle gangs, and youth gangs.  Real growth has been seen in the youth gangs, especially on the North Island.
<P>

1996 has been a year that has seen a major increase in gang violence.  In the past two months, there have been three gang-related drive-by shootings in the city of Christchurch, which is located on the South Island.  One innocent woman was shot and wounded, in one incident, as she sat in her car at a stop light.  She was caught in the crossfire between two rival gangs. Also on the South Island, the city of Invercargill has seen shootings, attempted bombings, gang fights and car rammings.
<P>

Sounding like a police spokesman from Boston, a New Zealand police detective related the following that is more than familiar to police officers in American cities -- the detective said, "Where gang headquarters are set up, the impact on the immediate neighborhood is just huge."  The detective is from the South Island city of Dunedin, where gang-related crimes have doubled in just the past nine months.  He added, "Real estate markets drop through the floor and people are scared in their own homes, which is very sad ... because that sort of thing has never really happened before."
<P>

Since this is a relatively new phenomena in New Zealand, police, there, really don't have a handle on the situation. It can be imagined that they may contact some U.S. law enforcement agencies for some advice to combat the problem. Like ... we really have our own gang problems in hand?
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights Reserved.
