<TITLE>Busy Fire/Haz-Mat Day in New York City</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from: EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Wednesday, January 31, 1996
<BR>
Vol.2 - 031
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<H2>FDNY EXPERIENCES BUSY DAY WITH HAZMAT AND FIRE OPERATIONS...</H2>
By Jim Fay  ENN NYC-NJ Correspondent
<P>

Tuesday, January 30, 1996 was an exceptionally busy work
day for firefighters and Manhattan Dispatchers of the FDNY,
with a steam explosion and several fires of some magnitude
all within the same period of time and area.
<P>

At approximately 1100 hrs., EST, the FDNY, as well as NYC*EMS
and NYPD Emergency Service Units responded to a report of
an explosion at the midtown Manhattan location of 3rd Ave. and
East 56 Street. This explosion turned out to be a steam
discharge in the street, but a fear of asbestos contamination
required a response of Fire Department and EMS HazMat specialized
response to the heavily traveled area, including the FDNY
DeCon, or Decontamination Unit.
<P>

About thirty minutes later, a residential high-rise fire at
The Bronx location of East 149 Street and Park Ave, directly
across from Lincoln Hospital,  started in the compactor
garbage disposal cute of the 27 story building.  This ultimately
required the response of a 2nd Alarm response from
the FD, as well a numerous BLS, ALS, and the Multi Patient
MerVan from EMS.  The building generally houses elderly persons
and all apartments had to be searched for possible occupants.
Late reports at the scene state that numerous persons required
treatment for smoke inhalation, but no exact number was available.
<P>

Before this fire was under control, a 2nd Alarm was transmitted
back in Manhattan, at the West Side location of Columbus Ave. and
West 104 St., for a gas-line fed fire in the basement of an
occupied multiple dwelling.  By this time FDNY companies from
Queens and Brooklyn were required to relocate to uncovered
firehouses in Manhattan.
<P>

While FDNY Dispatchers were still attempting to provide
adequate coverage for Manhattan, an "All Hands" fire in a
NYC Housing Authority Project at 55 LaSalle Street, near Broadway,
in Harlem, was being fought in a 30th floor apartment.
This fire resulted in one serious civilian injury, designated
as a "10-45 code 2" by the Fire Department.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights Reserved.
<P>
