<HEAD>
<TITLE>Streetgang "Franchises", Exporting Drugs</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted From: EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Sunday, January 21, 1996
<BR>
Vol.2 - 021
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>
<H2>STREET GANG FRANCHISES...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Managing Editor
<P>

In a recent study by criminologists at the University of Southern
California (USC), it was found that Chicago is second only to
Los Angeles as the leader in gang member exportation.  The number
one street gang in Chicago that exports gangbangers is The Gangster
Disciples.  With an estimated 30,000 members in Chicago, The
Gangster Disciples have taken a definite aggressive approach to
branching out to other cities in the United States.
<P>

Professor George Knox is the director of the National Gang Crime
Research Center at Chicago State University.  Knox says that Gangster
Disciple street gang activity can now be found in as many as 35
different states.
<P>

In a report that was issued in late 1995, the National Gang Crime
Research Center found that nearly 25 percent of 107 law enforcement
agencies in the State of Georgia had contact with Gangster Disciples
in their communities.  The same kind of numbers could also be found
in the States of Indiana, Iowa, Ohio and Wisconsin.
<P>

The main thing that is driving this exportation of gangbangers is
drugs -- and the money that can be made from the sale of drugs.
Professor Knox said that gangs discover opportunities to make
much more money in a city and they move in.  He said, "They see
there's nothing happening, see dollar signs, set up a prototype,
and they're up and running.  It's sort of like a McDonald's
operation, a franchise."
<P>

In August of 1993, police in Springfield, Missouri, uncovered a
large Gangster Disciple "franchise" in their community.  They
arrested an 18-year-old suspect from the southern Chicago suburb
of Harvey.  The suspect was arrogant enough to tell officers all
about the drug operation that he had been running.  One narcotics
investigator said, "He told me he was from a suburb of Chicago
and he had come to Springfield and had been selling crack cocaine.
He admitted that he was a member of the Gangster Disciples street
gang, that the gun he was carrying was to protect his money and
his investment."
<P>

Further investigation by the police in Springfield, Missouri,
came up with indictments against 32 people.  All who also
claimed to be Gangster Disciple members.  The drug operation
generated as much as $50,000 a month in profits.
<P>

What brought the street gang members to Springfield?  Well,
for one thing -- they found that they could sell the same rock of
crack cocaine that was selling for $10 to $25 dollars in
Chicago for $50 in Springfield.
<P>

Another Springfield narcotics investigator said, "They could sell
an ounce of crack in Chicago for $1,000.  Down here, they could
get $8,000 for that same ounce."
<P>
<HR>
To see a related 1992 ENN report on gang "pipelines":  <A HREF="/gangturf.htm"><B>Click here for the ENN Special Report on Drug Distribution and Small Town Exploitation</B></A>
<P>
