<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Gang Crimes; Govt. Wins Round One</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from: EmergencyNet NEWS Service (ENNFAX)
<BR>
Saturday, March 9, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 069
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>

<H2>U.S GOVERNMENT WINS ROUND ONE IN GANG TRIAL...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Editor
<P>

On Wednesday, United States Attorney Jim Burns said, "We view
this as a great first step.  But I can assure you that the battle
has just begun."  Burns said that after eight members of the
infamous Gangster Disciple street gang were convicted in a Chicago
federal court.
<P>

Prosecutors said that this was only the first step toward putting
the gang, that operates like corporation, out of business.  Despite
Wednesday's convictions and at least two trials to begin later this 
year, Chicago Police officials say that Chicago's largest street
gang still maintains its choke-hold on the illegal drug activity.
<P>

Donald Hilbring, the commander of the CPD Gang Crimes unit, said,
"If you indicted the head of IBM or Xerox, the corporation is still
functioning.  Nothing's crumbled."  Hilbring said that the gang
controls much of Chicago's South Side, its suburbs and and even
is involved in drug activity in several cities and towns in other
states. Wednesday's convictions were just the first test of the U.S. 
government's six-year investigation of the Gangster Disciples
code-named Operation Headache.
<P>

Eight defendants were convicted on Wednesday of drug conspiracy.
It is possible that the defendants will receive life sentences.
Four of the defendants were considered to be high-ranking "governors"
of the gang.  These governors that were convicted were Russell Ellis,
Keith McCain, Sherman Moore and Eric Wilson.  All were convicted of
conducting a criminal enterprise, which carries, in this case, a
mandatory life sentence.
<P>

One of the other defendants who was convicted was former Chicago
Police officer Sonia Irwin.  Irwin was even once a member of the
CPD Gang Crimes unit.  She was said to be romantically connected
to the number two man in the gang and had fronted what prosecutors
called, "Gang Central."  Irwin jointly owned a restaurant that was
used to conduct much of the gang's street business.
<P>

The BIG test and what will be considered the Super Bowl of this
six-year investigation will come on October 5th when the reputed
leader of the Gangster Disciples, Larry Hoover, goes on trial.
Hoover, who has been in prison for almost 25 years on a murder
conviction, was among 39 people who were indicted last summer.
<P>

After the convictions on Wednesday, the foreman of the jury that
found the defendants guilty told what helped the jury come to its
decision.  Larry Hoover and his co-horts were secretly tape
recorded during visits to the minimum security Vienna Correctional
Center.  The jury foreman said that the ability of Hoover to
control Chicago's largest street gang even though he has been in
prison since 1973 "boggled the mind."  According to unnamed sources, the government, in this first trial,
did not even use all of the evidence that it has at its disposal.
Additional evidence is planned to be revealed against Hoover in
subsequent trials.
<P>

During this last trial, the secret tape recordings of Hoover and
his gangbanger buddies gave a look behind the mindset of these
type of criminal individuals.  Hoover's number one assistant,
Gregory "Shorty G" Shell, was even surprised at Hoover's ability
to maintain not just control -- but STRONG control of the street
gang from prison.  In a conversation that was recorded in 1993,
Shell said to Hoover, "I'm a-tell you something, man, that the
biggest part amazes a lotta people about you that been gone for
20, 21 years and you ..."  "... Still in touch," Hoover finished.
Shell replied, "Still in touch like you ain't been nowhere."
<P>

Some of the conversations can be called disturbing.  Hoover and
Shell talked about how to corrupt youths and how to entice them
into the gang.  Their main sales pitch to kids was the material
rewards that drug-dealing brings to them. Shell said to Hoover, "I might give this guy a 9 or give this
regent 4 1/2.  So they, they can have ... nice clothes, nice shoes,
they pay their bills."  Shell was referring to common street terms
used for one-eighth and one-quarter of a kilogram of narcotics.
<P>

Hoover responded to Shell, "That way you bring them along with you,
that's the thang, you bring them along.  They look up, they gots
something.  They got now more than they ever had in life.  They
know this.  They know they wouldn't have anything without you."
What Hoover was in effect saying is that the appeal of being in the
gang, and what the government feels is insidious, is that -- 
Together, we can have riches.  Alone, you are nothing.
<P>

In another conversation Hoover became angry about finding out that
one of his "regents" had been beaten for not answering a page from
his superior.  Hoover, however, was not upset because the person
had been beaten, but gang protocol was not followed.  Hoover said
that the regent should have been "talked to first, then fined,
then his ass."
<P>

Authorities and prosecutors talked to many 11- and 12-year-olds
about why they joined the Gangster Disciples.  Most said it was
because of peer pressure. Prosecutor Ronald Safer asked several of these gangbangers the
following question: "Why do you follow Hoover?"  Safer said,
incredously, he received the same kind of reply -- a blank stare.
Safer said that was because they had never thought about the
question before.
<P>

And really who can blame these kids? Living a life of poverty, in substandard housing, with little education, and few prospects for the future, what choices do they have?   Faced with a choice of working at a fast-food restaurant for five dollars an hour or making $100
a night acting as a lookout for a drug dealer -- is it really
surprising which route many of the kids take?
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights reserved.
<P>
