<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>SARA/Right to Know Information</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>Three -- count 'em three -- different types of substances are subject to 
SARA:</H3>
<P>


1) Extremely Hazardous Substances;

2) Hazardous Chemicals; and

3) Toxic Chemicals.

We've talked about the "extremely hazardous substances."  We're now going to speak at length about "hazardous chemicals."  Keep in mind that ALL "extremely hazardous substances" are also "hazardous chemicals."  Even if you've reported your "extremely hazardous substances to the State Emergency Response Commission, you are still required to report them again as "hazardous chemicals."
<P>

SARA's reporting requirements for "hazardous chemicals" are what we 
typically associate with Right-To-Know information: who has how much of what 
hazardous chemicals, where they've got them, and what they can do to public 
health.
<P>
<HR>

In broad outline, SARA:
<P>

1) Defines what is a hazardous chemical;
<P>

2) Specifies which industries and businesses must report their hazardous 
chemicals;
<P>

3) Identifies the State and local groups to which reporting is to be made 
and provisions for public disclosure of information;
<P>

4) Provides for reporting information in three progressive stages with each 
stage requiring more information;
<P>

4) Sets deadlines for reporting;
<P>

5) Contains provisions for protecting the chemical identity of "trade 
secrets."
<P>

Lives will be saved or lost depending upon how successful a community is in 
reporting and managing this information.
<P>

<HR>
We'll need to discuss these in some depth.
<P>
So what's a "hazardous chemical"?
<P>

SARA says that they are the same "hazardous chemicals" that are subject to 
the OSHA hazard communication standard.
<P>

The OSHA hazard communication standard applies to "any chemical which is a 
physical or health hazard." THAT and a little common sense should see you 
through.
<P>

There's no list of hazardous chemicals.  Persons who import, manufacture or 
distribute chemicals which are physical or health hazards are required to 
provide appropriate warning labels and Material Safety Data Sheets when they 
sell the chemicals to third parties.
<P>

The receipt of an MSDS sheet with a shipment is usually a good indication 
that a chemical is hazardous.  Not always though.  Some companies send out 
MSDS sheets with substances (such as steel) listing toxic components 
(chromium).  Now the chromium in a steel sheet is unlikely to hurt anybody, 
but you may process it into a hazardous substance (like grind it into a fine 
powder).
<P>

Some chemical manufacturers send out MSDS sheets which say that a chemical 
is harmless.  That's done just so you don't think they've forgotten to 
notify you and to prevent unnecessary precautions.
<P>

Except for these limited circumstances, an MSDS sheet usually signals the 
existence of a physical or health hazard.
<P>
<HR>

OSHA considers a chemical to be a physical hazard if it's:
<P>

a) Flammable or combustible;
<P>

b) A compressed gas or explosive;
<P>

c) An oxidizer or organic peroxide;
<P>

d) Pyrophoric (capable of spontaneous ignition, e.g. white phosphorus); or,
<P>

e) Unstable or water reactive.
<P>

<HR>
"Health hazards" are identified as any chemical for which their is at least 
one valid scientific study which demonstrates either acute or chronic health 
effects in exposed employees.  Note that this includes chemicals which are 
hazardous only after long periods of exposure.  Carcinogens, mutagens, and 
chemicals which slowly attack target organs (kidneys, liver, etc.) are 
included.
<P>
<HR>

There are exceptions to the SARA (and OSHA) definition of hazardous 
chemicals:
<P>

a) Foods, colors, additives, drugs, and cosmetics regulated by the FDA;
<P>

b) Solids in manufactured items when chemical exposure is not likely to 
occur during normal use;
<P>

c) Substances which are present in the same form or concentration as a 
product packaged for use by the general public (e.g. the can of Drano you 
use on the company toilets);
<P>

d) Substances used in a research lab, hospital, or medical facility under 
the direct supervision of a qualified individual;
<P>

e) Substances being used in routine agricultural operations or fertilizers 
held by a retailer for sale to the ultimate customer.
<P>

The "hazardous chemicals" can be numbered in the tens of thousands.  For 
purposes of determining how many reports will be coming in, my state has 
been using an anticipated average of 200 "hazardous chemicals" per reporting 
entity.  Some corporations have told us that they have thousands on site.
<P>
<A HREF="/hzmtpage.htm"><B>Reurn to the Haz-Mat Operations Page</B></A>
<P>

</BODY>
</HTML>
