<HEAD>
<TITLE>FDNY Lt. Pays Ultimate Price</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<H3>FDNY ENDS YEAR IN TRAGEDY...</H3>
By Jim Fay,  ENN NYC/NJ Metro Correspondent
<P>

Lieutenant John M. Clancy was doing exactly what he
was suppose to do as the officer of Queens Ladder
Company 127, one of the first arriving ladder
companies: initiating a search.
<P>

Late reports are that an arrest has been made,
and Lieutenant Clancy was a victim of sabotage
of the floor of the fatal vacant building.
<P>

The two alarm fire, which occurred on Sunday morning,
December 31, at 0700 hrs.,EST, was in a building known
to be a vacant building. But to any experienced
firefighter, "vacant" does not mean "unoccupied."
Clancy knew that squatters usually stayed in
vacant buildings in NYC, either to live in or to
conduct drug activity.
<P>  

In any event, a search had to be made.  He went 
to the rear entrance of the building, entered 
the door, and the stairway landing collapsed 
underneath him, taking the 35-year-old Clancy 
into the raging fire that was in the basement. 
It is now reported that the landing was sabotaged 
to prevent other drug dealers from entering into 
this "drug den." A piece of linoleum was placed over a
large hole in the floor. When Clancy made
his first step on the "trap," he fell to the
basement.  Although he was immediately rushed
to the hospital, Clancy succumbed to his burns
and trauma injuries.
<P>

Lieutenant Clancy's exposure to the FDNY did not start
with his appointment as a firefighter. His father, Edward
Clancy, was a thirty-year veteran of the Fire Department,
retiring as a Deputy Chief from the old 10th Division
in Brooklyn and the 13th Division in Queens.
Edward Clancy died two years ago.  Lieutenant Clancy
is survived by his wife, who is six months pregnant
with their first child, and his mother.
<P>
**************************************************************************************
<BR>
Editors Note: It is now being reported that a suspect in this
arson fire is now in NYPD custody.  Crack houses or drug 
dens, such as this building are fairly common in many parts
of New York City. 
<P> 

A file of known drug houses is maintained in the FDNY's
Critical Information Dispatch System (CIDS).  The CIDS
program is able to provide fire companies critical information
about specific buildings.  Responding units are alerted to
dangerous or hazardous conditons that are not apparent from
the front of the building.  Booby-traps, such as what Lt. Clancy
fell through and discarded needles are only some of the hazards
that firefighters face in these type of buildings.
<P>
The funeral mass for Lt. Clancy will be on Thursday, January 4, 1996
at 1000 EST at Our Lady of Snows Church, located on Blue Point
Avenue in Blue Point, Long Island, New York.
<P>
ENN sends it's prayers and condolences to the family and friends of
Lt. Clancy...he paid the ultimate price while trying to keep the citizens of New York safe from the ravages of fire.
<P>
<A HREF="/firepage.htm"><B>Return to the ENN News Page</B></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>

