<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chicago Inferno Kills 4, More than 50 Hurt</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet News Service
<BR>
For Immediate Release: 01/18/96-10:20CST
<P>
<H2>THE INFERNO ON COTTAGE GROVE AVENUE...</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Managing Editor
<P>
Chicago firefighters are being called heroes for their efforts at a 5-11 Alarm fire on Box 222 at 3555 South Cottage Grove  Avenue on Chicago's South Side.  The fire started in a fifth floor apartment unit in a large 10-story brick 200-unit Chicago  Housing Authority (CHA) apartment building.  Very heavy fire was showing out the windows when firefighters first arrived on the scene at about 0325 CST.  Strong winds pushed the blaze out  into the fifth floor hallway.
<P>

The first job for firefighters was rescues.  Frightened people were hanging out of windows on all floors and several victims did jump. One firefighter said, "People were hanging out of windows all over."
<P>

The one word that has been used to describe the rescue efforts of  the CFD members has been, "heroic."  60 people were rescued from  the building.  As truck companies were raising their ladders to  windows, people reportedly jumped upon them.  Six aerial ladders and Squad 1's snorkel were used to rescue victims from windows.
<P>

Firefighter Bill Heenan reportedly made a miraculous catch of a child.  As Heenan was climbing up the ladder, a child was dropped from a window -- Heenan reached out and caught the child with one hand.  A similar rescue was also reportedly made by Firefighter Brian Rafferty.  In all, seven children were reportedly dropped from windows.
<P>

An Emergency Medical Services Plan Number Three brought 15 Chicago Fire Department ambulances to the scene.  A conflicting number of between 51 and 54 people were injured in this blaze. Included in the injured were two CFD members.  The victims were transported to nine area hospitals.  At last report, three victims were in serious condition, nine were in fair and eight were in good condition.  31 other people were treated and released. Despite the heroic efforts to save everyone, four people did die in this blaze.  One of the victims died from injuries sustained when she jumped from an upper floor.
<P>

It took firefighters about 90 minutes to bring this fire under control.  There was a Special Call for four additional truck  companies over the 5-11 Alarm assignment. It was a very hot fire with temperatures estimated at 1000 degrees (F).  Chicago Fire Commissioner Raymond Orozco said, "There was a tremendous  amount of heat.  You could compare this to a blowtorch."   A preliminary  report from fire investigators indicated that the cause of the blaze may  be careless use of smoking materials.
<P>
