<HEAD>
<TITLE>ATF/FBI Raids on Militia in Georgia</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet News Service
<BR>
Emergency Response & Research Institute
<BR>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 04/26/96-11:45CDT
<P>
<H2>Federal Agents Raid Bomb Factory; Two in Custody</H2>
By Clark Staten
<P>

Chicago, IL, April 26, 1996 (ENN)--Federal agents from the FBI
and ATF fanned out into rural central Georgia today to raid
several houses and an alleged militia "bomb factory".  Early
reports had indicated that the agents had uncovered a plot to
bomb several Olympic venues before or during the upcoming Summer
games. Contradictory reports are now coming from senior federal
law enforcement officials, who are now saying that "there is no
known connection with a threat to the Olympics." "Either way,"
an unidentified local sheriff's deputy said, "we have taken some
bombs off the streets that could have maimed or killed any
number of people."
<P>

Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms agents raided homes in
Crawford County, Georgia early today and at least two people
have been taken into custody. The detained individuals were
identified as "militia members" by an ATF spokesperson.  Also
reportedly taken into custody were several "bomb components"
that could be used to construct pipe bombs. Arrest warrants that
were used in the raids charged the militia members with
"conspiracy to possess and distribute explosive devices", in
violation of federal law.
<P>

Counter-Terrorist (CT) analysts and federal law enforcement
agencies have expressed their concerns, in the past several
months, about a possible domestic terrorism threat directed
against Atlanta and the Olympic venues. Several multi-agency
drills have been conducted in the past two weeks involving
bombings, poison gases, and biological agents. A variety of
special teams have been relocated and are said to be studying
the necessary intelligence to assist in Atlanta, should that be
necessary. All are said to be on a "high state of alert" for
either a domestic or international attack.
<P>

Whether or not the specific bombs and bombers involved in
today's arrests were the source of these fears may remain at
issue. But, one thing is certain. The FBI and local law
enforcement agencies have "pulled out all the stops" and are
utilizing numerous resources in an attempt to prevent or
mitigate any possible threat to the 1996 Olympic games.  Today's
action in Crawford County may have just been a preemptive
measure to reduce one of any number of possible threats as the
opening of the games draws nearer.
<P>
                      
(c) Emergencynet NEWS Service, 1996
<BR>
All rights reserved, except as assigned.
<BR>
Emergency Response & Research Institute
<BR>
6348 N. Milwaukee Ave., #312, Chicago, IL 60646
