<HEAD>
<TITLE>Drug King-Pins Arrest -Impact</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted From:
<BR>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service-ENNFAX
<BR>
Tuesday, January 23, 1996
<BR>
Vol.2 - 023
<P>
<B>LEAD STORY</B>
<BR>
<H2>LITTLE CHANGE EXPECTED AFTER ARREST OF DRUG KINGPIN...
</H2>
By Steve Macko, ENN Managing Editor
<P>

After the January 14th arrest of drug kingpin Juan Garcia Abrego,
experts say that the flow of cocaine into the United States may
only slow down for a short while.  But Abrego's drug rivals will battle
over his turf and then pick up the slack.  Overall, the recent 
arrest of Abrego will have little, if any, long-term effect.
<P>

Experts who keep an eye on the big drug cartels said that prior
to his arrest, Abrego's power had waned a little bit.  With him
gone and in prison in the United States, a power struggle will
develop to see who will gain control of the multi-million dollar
business.
<P>

Phil Jordan is a retired United States Drug Enforcement Administration
(DEA) agent in Dallas, Texas.  Jordan helped put together the case
that indicted Abrego in the early 1990's.  Jordan said, "A lot of
people will struggle to get Garcia Abrego's business.  But it will
take them years to amass the kind of power and fortune he enjoyed.
He was one of the big guys."
<P>

Because of recent blows that have been brought against the infamous
Colombia Cali cartel, Mexican drug smugglers have emerged as a
powerful force in the world drug market.  It is said that the 
Mexicans are now responsible for at least 75 percent of all the
cocaine that is smuggled into the United States.
<P>

With the arrest of Abrego, Mexico hopes to gain recertification in
March from the United States in the war on drugs.  The United States
State Department and Congress rate countries each year for their
cooperation.  Congress then awards U.S. aid accordingly, based upon
a country's rating.
<P>

The arrest of Abrego is seen as the most important drug arrest in
Mexico since the arrest of drug kingpin Miguel Angel Felix Gallardo,
who was called the "Godfather of Mexican Drug Trafficking", in 1989.
Experts said that even after Gallardo's arrest, it only put a small
dent in the drug smuggling from Mexico until rivals finished a
battle over his territory.  Within a few years, everything was back
to normal.  And experts say that the same thing will happen after
the arrest of Abrego.
<P>

Professor Peter Lupsha of the University of New Mexico studies the
illegal drug business.  Lupsha said, "Garcia Abrego's rivals are
celebrating."  According to the U of New Mexico professor, Amado
Carrillo Fuentes, who is the leader of the Juarez cartel and is
said to be the number one drug smuggler in Mexico, has the most to
gain with the arrest of Abrego.
<P>

Fuentes is known as "The Lord of the Skies."  This is because his
cartel often uses old passenger jets to smuggle the Colombian
cocaine into Mexico.  Fuentes has risen to power very quickly
and is said to have learned a lot from the Cali cartel.
<P>

Lupsha said, "Nothing changes for drug trafficking.  The arrest of
Juan Garcia Abrego is simply cleaning up on the last Mexican
administration and passing the baton.  The corruption and trafficking
will continue."
<P>
<A HREF="/polcpage.htm"><B>Return to the ENN News Page</B></A>
</BODY>
</HTML>

