<HEAD>
<TITLE>Toxic Chemicals; Korea and Japan</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from EmergencyNet NEWS Service (ENNFAX)
<BR>
Saturday, April 13, 1996
<BR>
Vol. 2 - 104
<P>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>
<P>
<HR>
Editor's Note: Ever since Monday, 8 April 1996, when ENN
reported that Japanese authorities had arrested a man for
smuggling dangerous chemicals that could be used to make 
the nerve gas sarin to North Korea (ENN2-099), analysts
at ERRI have been saying, "Something is not right with
this story."
<P>

It now appears that other analysts have been saying the
same thing.  We offer the following theory that was
written by Ronald W. Lewis, who is the Chief Military
Analyst with The Intelligyst Group.  We thank The
Intelligyst Group for allowing us to republish this paper.
<P>
We offer this only as a theory, but many of the points offered
seem to make more sense than what has been offered, so far, by
press reports or other authorities.  ERRI analysts believe this to be a
very workable theory.  Above everything else, ERRI analysts
believe that the North Koreans may be playing a very
dangerous game and ERRI offers a warning to the South Koreans
and the Japanese about the possibility of a forthcoming chemical attack.
<P>
<HR>
<H2>POSSIBLE NORTH KOREAN BEGINNING STRATEGY...</H2>
By Ronald W. Lewis
<BR>
Chief Military Analyst
<BR>
The Intelligyst Group
<P>

On Monday, April 8, Japanese authorities arrested a shipping
clerk,  an ethnic Korean, in Kobe, Japan.  This individual
"admitted" to sending batches of chemicals which are
ingredients of the nerve agent sarin to North Korea.  As many
of you may recall, sarin was the nerve agent employed in the
March 20, 1995 Tokyo subway gas attack.   Since North Korea
has more than enough production capacity for sarin, it is highly
unlikely that this individual was shipping sarin component
chemicals TO North Korea but was rather, in all likelihood,
caught with chemicals he had received FROM North Korea.
<P>

It has been a longstanding contention of this analyst that
North Korea--and possibly China--was behind the gas attacks
in Japan, as a method of coercing the Japanese and
blackmailing them into not supporting US forces in time of war
with North Korea or China.  The continuing episodes of gas
attacks and incidents in Japan since then have all occurred on
or about periods of heightened tension over the DMZ or Taiwan.
<P>

As tensions continue to mount in North Korea, it occurs to this
analyst that the perfect way in which to launch an invasion of
South Korea is to set off gas attacks in Seoul and other South
Korean cities, much as was done in Tokyo last March.
<P>

If this should occur, morale at the front lines would probably
crumble as soldiers desert to protect and check on the welfare
of their families.  If the attacks are relatively small in scope,
with a relatively low body count, a terrified public would likely
withdraw support any military action, fearing more such attacks.
<P>

This was one reason the attacks in Japan were designed to kill
only small numbers of people when, instead, they could have
annihilated very large numbers.  Large casualty counts demand
swift retaliation, to bring the fight home to the enemy before he
can kill more of your own people.  Small numbers of casualties
usually result in "pay-offs" of the victims' families and a flurry of
diplomatic deal-making to prevent further attacks.  This happened
in Japan.  North Korea might try it with the South.
<P>

However, it is also possible that the South would retaliate
severely, prompting the need for large chemical attacks by the
North, or the North may just simply go all-out, hoping that a
large assault in the initial stages will destroy South Korean and
US resolve to fight.
<P>

Another option would be to set off a new series of limited
attacks in Japan, forcing them to shut down US bases and
ports or face all-out chemical assault.  North Korea DID
threaten Japan with chemical attacks in 1994.
<P>

The inability of US aircraft and US ships in Japan to deploy
would be a huge crisis during a war in Korea.  If this is
successful, it is likely that North Korea will then attempt a
land invasion with conventional weapons would soon follow.
If the North Koreans were to prove successful without the need
for direct Chinese intervention, as in November 1950, China
would probably then commit other forces to a takeover of
Taiwan.
<P>

The key is that the Japanese attacks have already demonstrated
that a few small bags of a nerve agent, employed in the right
environment, can cause massive chaos.  It is well established
that North Korean agents are in South Korea.  In fact, it was
only a few months ago that 20,000 South Korean troops and
police conducted a manhunt for a few infiltrators who attempted
to extract a long-time mole whom had been planted there years
ago.  Airports, subways and other areas critical to national
defense or filled with large numbers of people are likely targets
if such deep-cover agents wished to wreak the most havoc.
<P>

Finally, it should be noted that within a day after the
March 20, 1995 Tokyo attack, office workers in a Seoul
office building of an American insurance company were
overcome by mysterious fumes.  The rescue workers who
responded were equipped with chemical warfare protective
garments, not something you normally wear when checking
out a supposed air conditioning coolant leak. 
<P> 

Later in the
summer of 1995, the LA TIMES reported that Disneyland
was an intended target of cult members intending to strike
with sarin.  The Seoul incident may have been a test but it,
along with the planned assault on Disneyland, may have been
a signal to the US, South Korean and Japanese governments.
It would be wise for South Korean security agents to increase
their surveillance of the types of areas where sarin--and the
other agents employed in Japan--were placed.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996
<P>
