<HEAD>
<TITLE>Haz-Mat News Briefs</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from ENNFAX, Vol. 2, No. 102, 04/11/96
<BR> 
<H2>Haz-Mat/Fire News Briefs</H2>
<IMG SRC="/NEWSBRF.GIF">
<P>
<B>Detroit...</B>
<P>
By Gary Baumgarten
<BR>
Michigan Public Safety Network
<P>

A huge fire at the Marathon refinery in southwest Detroit created so
much smoke that state police were forced to shut down nearby I-75
for a short time. Witnesses heard a series of small explosions when the
fire in the refinery's main crude oil unit began. Company firefighters
were joined by counterparts from Detroit and neighboring River
Rouge and Melvindale in keeping an adjacent tank farm cool and in
putting foam on the flames until they were able to turn a valve cutting
off the flow of oil to the fire. Everyone was accounted for and there
were no injuries.
<P>

A two-alarm fire ripped through an abandoned Detroit bowling alley
on Six Mile and Woodward. Smoke was seen from miles away.
Firefighters were expected to remain on the scene throughout the
night for extensive overhauling.
<P>

Dozens of grass fires have kept firefighters busy this week throughout
Michigan's Saginaw Valley and elsewhere in the state. Dry weather is
being blamed for the rash of early spring brush fires. Firefighters have
also been battling grass fires in Kalamazoo, Kent, Livingston,
Muskegon and Ottawa Counties.
<P>
<HR>
<B>Montana...</B>
<BR>
Via ENN e-mail
<P>

Montana is becoming a big news state.  On Thursday morning, five
cars of a freight train derailed near the western Montana town
of Alberton.  The five tank cars derailed at about 0400 MDT and
were said to contain chlorine.  At least one of the train cars
overturned and began to leak.
<P>

At least ten people were transported to area hospitals complaining
of breathing problems.  The town of Alberton with its 400 residents
was evacuated.  Interstate 90 was closed for three miles in each
direction.  The Missoula Hazardous Materials Team was on the
scene of the incident.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights reserved.
