<HEAD>
<TITLE>NJ Haz-Mat; Tanker Hit by Train</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
For Immediate Release: 01/10/96-09:00EST
<BR>
<B>New Jersey...</B>
<P>
<H3>Gasoline Tanker Hit by Train in  Bergen County</H3>
By Jim Fay, ENN NYC-NJ Metro Correspondent
<P>
A fully-loaded gasoline tanker-truck was struck (yesterday) by a freight
train in a populated, residential neighborhood in Bergen County,
NJ, near the George Washington Bridge on Tuesday.
<P>

At 1100 hrs., EST, the Bogota Volunteer Fire Department
responded  to the struck tanker at Ft. Lee Road and River Road.
Upon arrival, firefighters observed the tanker portion of the
truck overturned, laying on it's side immediately adjacent to an
operating neighborhood gas station.  The tanker did not rupture
and there were no apparent leaks.  The truck had just left a Hess
Oil Company holding tank facility, a major gasoline storage area,
about 500 feet west of the railroad crossing. The truck was hit by 
a northbound Susquahanna Railroad freight train, a small railroad that travels through NJ, up into NY State.
<P>

A call went out for HazMat personnel from numerous surrounding
volunteer fire departments, as well as HazMat and Rescue Company
firefighters from the paid departments of Teaneck, Englewood, and
the county seat of Hackensack, NJ.  In addition, a multi-unit
Bergen County Dept. of Health HazMat team responded and
spearheaded the operation.
<P>

The residential neighborhood of private homes and garden
apartments immediately around the incident was evacuated and
those people were taken to Bogota High School and assisted
by Disaster personnel from the Bergen County Chapter of the
American Red Cross.
<P>

At approximately 1230 hrs., the off-loading operation started.
It was undetermined how long the operation would take, but heavy
foam lines surrounded the tanker and would continue until all
of the product was safely removed.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights reserved.
