<TITLE>Baltimore 12 Alarm fire</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<H2>Baltimore Firefighters Fight 12 Alarm Blaze</H2>
<P>
<BR>
By Steve Macko
<BR>
11/09/95 (ENN) --Firefighters in BALTIMORE, MARYLAND, fought a 
spectacular 11 Alarm fire at Hollins and Calverton in Baltimore's southwest
district.  At about 0010 EST, fire started in a 3-story brick vacant warehouse.  
The huge blaze was apparently started by some homeless people who were trying 
to keep warm.  The original fire building was fully involved and it 
was reported that firefighters encountered water problems.
<P>  
The fire reportedly communicated to three other large exposure buildings.  
All of the exposure buildings were described as warehouse-type buildings.  
One was described as being 10-stories and another was 6-stories.  One 
of the buildings was called the Hollins Street Exchange, which is a 
block-long complex that was occupied by 50 small businesses.  The original fire 
building, the 6-story and 10-story buildings were believed to be destroyed.
<P>  
The third exposure building was well involved with fire through the roof.  
It took Baltimore firefighters about seven hours to bring this blaze under 
control.  Baltimore Fire Chief Herman Williams said that this fire was
the largest in the city in recent memory.  Three firefighters suffered
minor injuries and mutual aid from Baltimore's suburbs was required.
<P>
(c) Emergencynet NEWS Service, 1995, All rights reserved.
<BR>
