<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Historical Perspective-Mid-East Terror</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE: 1400CDT-07/29/94
<P>
<H2>The Latest Wave of Terror...</H2>
By Clark Staten
<P>
Chicago, IL, July 29, 1994 -- There may, in actuality, be no rational
explanation of the most recent wave of violent attacks against
Israel and her allies.  On the other hand, by gaining a
historical perspective, we may be able to better understand the
issues that have resulted in the current dilemma.  The roots of
the problem date back to May, 14, 1948, when the British
Mandate, and control of the "Holy Lands", expired.  A guerrilla
war between Jewish settlers and previous Palestinian inhabitants
has continued, almost unabated, since that time.  Territorial
claims to Jerusalem and the surrounding areas have been
presented by many groups, but the force of arms has prevailed,
and Israel has repeatedly been able to defend its sovereignty. 
<P>
<HR>
<B>Suez Canal Crisis</B>
<P>

1956 brought the Suez Canal Crisis, and an Israeli advance
into the Sinai, prompted by English and French complicity in a
plan to take the strategic canal away from the Egyptians.  The
fledgling Israeli Defense Forces (IDF) performed admirably and
territorial gains resulted. 
<P>
<HR>
<B>1967 Sinai War</B>
<P>

In 1967, Palestinian raiders from Syria increasingly put the
lives of Jewish immigrants in danger.  Encouraged by the
U.S.S.R., Egypt, and its charismatic leader Gamal Nasser, was
thought to have "expansionist" tendencies, and a desire to
invade Israel.  As 100,000 Egyptian troops massed on the Sinai,
Israel took the only action available to prevent certain
defeat...on June 5, 1967, they attacked.  A brilliantly planned
air attack destroyed almost the entire Egyptian air force as it
sat on the ground.  By gaining air superiority, the Israelis
were then able to maneuver their tank corps with impunity, not
fearing Egyptian air attacks.  A series of armored cavalry and
tank task forces then advanced rapidly and surrounded or cut-off
Egyptian defenders.  Six days later, it turned into a rout, and
the Israelis gained both territory and the respect of other
military forces in the region.
<P>
<HR>
<B>Attack on the Golan Heights </B>
<P>

By October 6, 1973, Egypt had all but forgotten its devastating
defeat at the hands of the Israelis.  Again encouraged by the
Soviet Union, Nasser and Anwar Sadat decided that the time had
come to again attempt to demonstrate that Egypt and the Arabs
were stronger than Israel.  Encouraged by massive amounts of
Soviet military aid, and hundreds of T54 and T55 tanks provided
by the U.S.S.R., the Egyptians believed that they could easily
defeat the smaller Israeli army. They began their assault on Yom
Kippur, the Jewish Day of Atonement.
<P>  

The Egyptian aggression met with initial success, largely due to
a failure of Israeli intelligence. They failed to believe that
Egypt would undertake another war so soon after their previous
defeat.  For three days, the Israelis suffered heavy losses,
both of men and materials.  The Egyptians, however, also
suffered the pains of their attack.  Massive armored assaults
continued, with Israel eventually scoring a major victory on the
Golan Heights.  Both sides were resupplied; Israel by the United
States, and Egypt and her allies by the Soviet Union. By October
23rd, it was obvious that the IDF had once again prevailed.  The
Israelis had again defended their homeland.
<P>
<HR>
<B>Israeli/Egypt Peace Agreement</B>
<P>

By 1979, Israel and Egypt had begun to resolve their differences
and negotiate a settlement to the possession of disputed lands
in the Sinai and the West Bank.  A historic Israeli-Egyptian
peace treaty was finally worked out and signed at Camp David in
the United States.  It signaled the first possibility of Israel
bargaining away land for peace.  Further, it strengthened a
relationship between the United States and Egypt. 
Unfortunately, it also stirred the wrath of the PLO and other
extremist groups that claimed Israel as their "homeland".  The
stage was set for continued negotiations by Israel and further
terrorist acts by those that would attempt to defeat her.
<P>
<HR>
<B>Problems in Lebanon</B>
<P>

During the 70's and early 80's, Lebanon became a "hotbed" or
revolutionary thought and action.  Conflicts between various
religious "surrogate" military forces embroiled the formerly
placid resort country into a place torn by civil strife and
religious fervor.  In keeping with this migration, members of
the PLO, Islamic Jihad, Black September(Abu Nidal Organization),
PFLP, and dozens of other Islamic and Palestinian "freedom
movements" emigrated to Lebanon and set up bases. Beirut itself
became a battleground for conflicts between the various
religious and nationalist organizations.  Soon the entire
country was involved in the anarchy, and several elected
government have fallen or their leaders assassinated.  Cross
border raids, into Israel, also began and escalated.
<P>

The United States has been inextricably involved in both
counter-terrorism and the Middle-East situation since a failed
mission to Beirut that resulted in the destruction of a U.S.
Marine Barracks on October 23rd, 1983, and the deaths of 241
Marines.  Concurrent with the attack on the U.S. "peacekeepers"
was a devastating attack on as French Foreign Legion Compound
nearby. Several dozen French paratroops also died on that
fateful day. The day of the Shi'ite suicide truck bomb had begun.
<P>

The mid-to-late 80's brought continued terrorist attacks against
Israel, on her border with Lebanon.  Terrorist attacks let to
military reprisals and incursions by Israel.  Moslem extremists
and PLO sympathizers carried out skyjackings, bombings, and
street riots against Israel and her allies.  Nations like Iraq,
Iran, Libya, and Syria were soon tied to complicity in terrorist
acts against Israel and the countries that supported her.  Both
the tempo and ferocity of the aggressions seemingly increased
with each passing year.
<P>  

America and her sphere of influence continued to prompt Israel
to make peace with her neighbors.  Both military and financial
incentives were given to Israel to encourage less militant
actions and reward diplomatic initiatives that might lead to
peace.  Yet, both internal and external conflicts prevented many
Israelis from adapting a peaceful stance towards their Arab
neighbors.  They had suffered far to many casualties, during
their forty (40) year struggle for independence and sovereignty,
to easily give back the land that had been won with blood.  The
negotiations, although cautious, continued throughout the
Middle-East.
<P>
<HR>
<B>Persian Gulf War</B>
<P>

During the 1991 Persian Gulf War, Israel displayed the greatest
restraint in the history of the often beleaguered country.  Even
though they were repeated struck by Iraq's SCUD missiles, they
refused to retaliate, largely because of requests and
reassurances from the United States that their inaction would
best serve the Allied Coalition in it's overall goal of
defeating Iraq.  The Persian Gulf conflict also cemented
relationships between Israel and several of her Arab neighbors,
lessening tensions and improving diplomatic ties.
<P>

Strangely enough, the development of these diplomatic and
financial ties may have further "fanned the fires" of radical
Islamic Fundamentalism.  A Washington-brokered 1993 Peace Accord
between Israel and the PLO seems to have been the impetuous of
the latest round of terrorist atrocities.  As the likelihood of
a peaceful subdivision of Israel came to fruition, the radicals
began calls for a complete subjugation of Israel and total
annexation of the country. Several Palestinian "splinter
groups", not represented by the PLO, were not satisfied with a
"limited self-rule" agreement for parts of Israel...they wanted
the whole country.  Since then, there has been a tremendous
increase in the number of terrorist incidents directed against
the Israelis and her allies.  Which brings us to the present.
<P>
<HR>
<B>The Rise of Iran and Islamic Fundamentalism; <BR>
A New Kind of Threat</B>
<P>

It should be noted that concurrent with the historic struggle
for a Palestinian homeland, a major "Islamic Revolution"
occurred in Iran.  Although the Iranians may have supported the
basic principals of the return of Israel to the Palestinians,
they also set out on an "expansionist" campaign of their own. 
Beginning in 1987, the Intifada, or Holy War, was begun, with
the expressed intent of exporting the Iranian brand of
Fundamentalist Moslem religion to the rest of the Middle-East
and even the world.  The Khomeini regime' also chose Israel as
an enemy, further compounding and expanding conflicts in the
region.
<P>

Israel's fight against Iranian-backed terrorist organizations is
probably the most complex problem facing the world today.  The
organizational structure of the many extremist splinter groups
is a bewildering maze of interlocking "cells" that may act as
surrogates of Iran or independently, as the leader of each group
may see fit. Although the weapons, explosives, and training may
have been provided to each group by Iran, the actual control of
each group is probably a "local" decision.
<P>  

Admittedly, Iran may have influence with hundreds of these types
of small groups, and even be able to encourage them to undertake
specific terrorist acts, Iran doesn't have absolute authority
over their actions.  This very fact complicates the possibility
of apprehension of the terrorists, or military revenge against a
given country.  Iran has what is called, in diplomatic and
intelligence circles, "deniable plausibility".  In other words,
they can honestly deny direct involvement, even though they may
have supplied all of the necessary elements and religiously
condoned the action.
<P>

It is believed that this is the case in recent bombings in
Argentina, Panama, and London, England.  The organization, or
organizations, responsible for these atrocities may have no
"direct traceable link" with Iran, even though they may have
been previously paid, equipped, and encouraged by Iran.  Each of
these belligerences has probably been carried out by a small
team of experts, often from different "extremist" groups, who
were assembled for the purpose of committing the specific act. 
Almost always, this is done with the assistance of a local
accomplice or accomplices, who are responsible for acquiring
equipment, weapons, explosives, and vehicles.  In each case,
however, we see one or more "fanatics", who are Moslem zealots
and prepared to die for the cause of Islamic expansionism.
<P>

The organizational structure of these "mission specific"
terrorist groups provides for a maximum of security, in that the
members don't even know each other, should they be caught and
interrogated.  Secondarily, it further complicates the process
of establishing responsibility for the act.  A typical example
would include the World Trade Center Bombing, which included
"experts" from several countries.  In some cases, their only
common element was an Islamic zeal to cause damage to "The Great
Satan", that is the United States. Thus, the problem confronting
the both Israel and the United States at the time of this
report. 
<P>
<HR>
<B>Threats Against the United States </B>
<P>

Both the U.S. State Department and FBI have reportedly issued
warnings, within the past six hours, that they have received a
"credible threat" against Jewish targets within the United
States.  Huge sand trucks have been moved to block the front of
the Israel embassy in New York City.  The Israeli Consulate is
Washington, DC is said to be on "full-alert", with additional
barricades installed and parking prohibited in the area.  A
senior emergency service official, in New York City, says that
Fire, Police, and EMS services have adapted an "increased state
of alert" there, and are awaiting further information about the
potential threat.
<P>
Most counter-terrorist analysts are presently urging extreme
caution, but also don't want to unnecessarily alarm the general
populace with unconfirmed reports of possible terrorist acts. 
In general, local, state, and federal officials seem to be
taking the threat seriously, but with reserved optimism that a
catastrophic event can be avoided by preparedness.  So...the
country waits, in heightened awareness, for the heinous act that
everyone hopes will never come.
<P>
		     
