<TITLE>Haz-Mat in Colorado Mountains</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
For Immediate Release: 13:25CST-02/21/96
<BR>
EmergencyNet News Service
<P>

<H2>Train Derailment and Sulphuric Acid Leak in Leadville, CO</H2>
By Clark Staten, ENN
<P>
Chicago, IL, February, 21, 1996, (ENN)--According to the Colorado State Patrol, there are two confirmed fatalities in a train derailment and toxic material spill that occurred today near Leadville, CO. Both of the dead are believed to be Southern Pacific Railroad employees, who were aboard the train at the time of the derailment. The accident occured at approx. 06:00a.m. this morning, near U.S. Highway 24, between Leadville and Minturn, Colorado.
<P>
Twenty-five (25) cars of the mixed load freight train left the track and several cars overturned. Two of those cars are believed to be leaking sulphuric acid onto nearby Highway 24.  A toxic gas cloud was reportedly formed as the spilled sulphuric acid mixed with snow and began to react. At least one person was admitted to the nearby Vail Valley Medical Center with respiratory difficulties, and "several others" were treated for eye and breathing irritation.
<P>
Several nearby homes and businesses were evacuated as a a special hazardous materials spill team attempted to control the spill and limit the spread of the gas cloud. Highway 24, itself, was reportedly contaminated and closed by State Patrol officers, as the firefighters worked to mitigate the emergency. Traffic congestion was also reported, as Interstate Highway 70 was previously closed by a snowslide and Highway 24 was being used as an alternative route.
<P>
The cause of the accident has not been established, but is under intensive investigation following a rash of train crashes and derailments in other parts of the country in recent days.  The Avalanche Information Center of Colorado speculated that the crash was caused by 16 inches of new snow and a snowslide that may have covered the tracks.  A State Patrol spokesperson said that "all theories" regarding the calamity would be given consideration, but that it was to early in the investigation to reach any conclusions.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights Reserved.
