<HEAD>
<TITLE>Haz/Mat-News Briefs-03/27/96</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
EmergencyNet News-03/27/96-15:00CST
<P>
<IMG SRC="/NEWSBRF.GIF">
<H2>Haz-Mat News Briefs</H2>

<B>Indiana...</B>
<P>

A powerful explosion that could be felt as far away as 30 miles
ripped through a steel plant in Portage, Indiana, on Wednesday
morning.  Three people are reported dead and eight others were
injured.  The blast occurred at 0708 CST at the Beta Steel plant,
located in Porter County, east of Chicago.
<P>

Preliminary reports are that an electrical explosion triggered a
gas explosion that knocked out a wall and caused a partial roof
collapse in different areas of the large 5-story metal-clad
building. An investigation continies regarding the involvement of a 
large water containment vessel that could also have been involved 
in the incident.  There was little or no ensuing fire.
<P>

A supervisor at the plant said that a tank located in the basement 
of the building that held water or hydralaulic fluid under pressure
had exploded.  The supervisor described, "All of a sudden there was
a huge explosion, like a time bomb.  Everything went kaboom."
<P>

Several employees were in a locker room when the roof collapsed and 
narrowly escaped serious injury or death. According to EMS sources, 
they were taken to several area hospitals, most in good condition. 
At least two employees underwent surgery for their injuries.
<P>
<HR>
<B>New Jersey...</B>
<P>
A central New Jersey industrial gas plant was allowed to burn
on Tuesday because firefighters were unable to use water on the
blaze.  The fire started at about 0900 EST at the Hunterdon
Industrial Gas plant located on the Delaware River, just outside
of Frenchtown, New Jersey.  No injuries were reported in the
incident.
<P>  

Firefighters could not put water on the blaze because of the
chemicals involved, which included helium, acetylene, propane
and oxygen.  The fire was allowed to burn itself out.  200 homes
within a half-mile radius of the plant were evacuated.
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All Rights reserved.
<P>
