<HEAD>
<TITLE>The "Public" out of "Public" Services</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Excerpted from: EmergencyNet NEWS Service
<BR>
Saturday, February 10, 1996
<BR>
Vol.2 - 041
<BR>
<B>**LEAD STORY**</B>

<H2>"COMMERCIALIZATION" TAKES "PUBLIC" OUT OF PUBLIC SAFETY??</H2>
By Jim Fay, ENN NYC-NJ Metro Correspondent
<P>

Firefighters and fire officers from several paid fire
departments have rallied to the support of paid and volunteer
firefighters in Westchester County, New York. Recently, a
contract was signed with a private corporation, who will set up 
and run a local fire department. The company, Rural/Metro 
Corporation of Scottsdale, Arizona,  is known nationwide as 
a company that is able to establish emergency service systems
in towns and corporate facilities. Rural/Metro claims to save 
the towns money by eliminating administrative overhead and 
management "headaches" involving municipal emergency workers, such as firefighters.
<P>

Rural/Metro has set up a fire department in Rye Brook, NY,
a village approximately 20 miles north of NYC.  Rye Brook
was previously contracting with an adjacent town of Port Chester 
to provide this coverage, and paying them about a third of the 
funds required of Port Chester to run its entire FD.  However, one 
thing that Rural/Metro has encountered in NY, that was not a problem 
anywhere else, is the support of strong unions of the paid drivers 
of the Port Chester Fire Department, and the large unionized  
membership of the various fire departments in other cities within 
Westchester County.
<P>  
Rural/Metro is not a union organization, and can pay its employees
substantially less than its counterparts in the paid fire
departments.  Many of the paid fire department members are
residents of Westchester County, and feel that, not only is the
"privatization" of a fire department a threat to their jobs,
but may cause a compromise of their own safety and that of their
families.   According to news reports, Rural/Metro firefighters
allegedly will not receive the basic hourly wage requirements of 
volunteer fire fighters in NYS.
<P>
Rural/Metro's business base has been primarily out in the west,
where small towns have developed, but the population cannot
sustain a paid department, or the population is made up of
retirees, unable to perform firefighting operations in a
voluntary capacity.The three-year Rye Brook contract is the
first contract in the northeast, where paid departments, as well
as paid/volunteer departments with ample volunteer members, exist.
Port Chester, the town that had been providing volunteer members
for Rye Brook's coverage, is an older town which still has names
such as "Reliance Hose Company" and "Putnam Engine & Hose 
No. 2," over the doors of their firehouses that were built in the
1880's, and where members have maintained a heritage and esprit 
de'corps. The corporate fire department, firefighters feel, has no
attachment to the community it serves, and the town will
suffer from it.
<P>

While other departments' unions are not as strong, their members
are just as vocal about the privatized operations. The privatized
fire departments  "...are no longer there to benefit the community,
but rather to benefit only their stock holders," says Captain Rob
Ullinger, a 16-year veteran of the Kent, Ohio, Fire Department,.
with  a "...decrease of service to the customer (the community)."
Ullinger calls it the "commercialization" of firefighting,
an occupation known for its dedication to, and stabilizing of,
a community. Kirk Harless, a firefighter/paramedic in South Dakota
called the fire service a "brotherhood," and "not run like a
(commercial) company, " referring to Rural/Metro's need to
maintain corporate profits. Rural/Metro has, in fact,
proven that it can make a profit and has become a worthwhile 
stock portfolio acquisition for investors.
<P>

Recently, Paradise Valley, Arizona, approved a contract with
Rural/Metro.  In the contract, Rural/Metro will be responsible for
the billing and collection of fees from home and property owners,
in lieu of taxes.  This was called a form of  "coercion and
intimidation" by Councilwoman Phyllis Sears, of Paradise Valley,
since it will be up to Rural/Metro to privately enforce the contract for
basic fire protection.
<P>  

However, this contract also calls for Rural/Metro to provide quarterly reports, estimates of water use, and fire prevention education, and a promise to build a second fire station. In addition, the company will provide ambulance
service for the town.  While Rural/Metro will collect the fees,
it will pay the town a quarterly license fee of $5000, or $20,000
a year, and use the collected fees for the running of the
emergency services.  This all appears to be a rather appealing
situation to a small government entity,  because it provides a
necessary service without the need of a government bureaucracy.
<P>
While it is not answered in the reports on this contract, a
question arises as to what the company does if a property owner
becomes in arrears in the fees. What happens if several of
property owners are in arrears?  Will they still get their fire
protection? If the property is abandoned, do only the fee-paying
exposures get protection?  Since the government is not collecting
taxes for this operation, can they step in on behalf of the
emergency service provider...or for that matter, for the homeowner?
While these questions may have been addressed in individual 
contracts, the details are generally not known. This may be one of the 
discouraging aspects of the commercialized service.
<P>

"The only things that are for sure is death and taxes,"  says
the old saw.  But, what has always been "sure" and taken for
granted, is that government intervention will occur when disaster strikes.
If the various units of government are not in the disaster business 
anymore, and someone who requires a profit every quarter is, then 
it would seem prudent for citizens to re-examine their priorities and 
be sure that they understand what their expectations can be.
<P>

<B>In the interest of fairness, EmergencyNet News hereby issues an open invitation to Rural/Metro and/or their corporate officers to address these concerns and present their side of this issue. Rural/Metro or other interested parties are invited to send replies to Mr. Fay at enn@emergency.com. Pertinent responses will be published here in the future.</B>
<P>
(c) EmergencyNet News Service, 1996, All rights Reserved.
<P>
