<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>IAFC-EMS Report By Gary Ludwig</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY> 
THE FOLLOWING IS A REPRINT FROM THE INTERNATIONAL ASSOCIATION OF FIRE CHIEFS NEWSLETTER 
<BR>            
<H3>"ON SCENE" </H3>
<BR>
     THE FOLLOWING ARTICLE IS WRITTEN FOR THE EMS MEMBERSHIP SECTION. PLEASE PASS ON TO OTHER FIRE AGENCIES AND FOR MEMBERSHIP INFORMATION IN THE IAFC-EMS SECTION, CONTACT 703-273-0911
<P>                         
<H3>   THESE TRULY ARE EXCITING TIMES!</H3>
<BR>
                         Gary G. Ludwig, MS, EMT-P
<P>
Some of most exciting news I can deliver is the stage is set to develop the largest fire-based EMS system in the United States with some 200+ ambulances.  If everything goes smooth, New York City EMS will be merged with NYFD in the near future.  I have had a chance to look at the proposal and speak with Fire Commissioner Howard Safir.  Commissioner Safir tells me that he fully expects to have EMS merged into the fire service by the first of the new year.  He further added, "this merger will introduce a new facet to New York City never seen before.
 A multi- tiered emergency medical care system which will increase our out-of-hospital cardiac arrest survival rates."  He cited a recent fire in Queens where one of the first-due engines who had been trained as first responders found four children in cardiac arrest.  Resuscitative efforts were begun and all four children survived.  As it turns out, they were the children of a firefighter.
<P>
    
I also spoke with Deputy Commissioner Dolan who wrote the plan.  I must note it is a well-thought-out and written plan.   Deputy Commissioner Dolan tells me he relied very heavily on the experiences of other fire-based EMS systems from across the country while developing the proposal.  In essence, he found what worked and did not work elsewhere.  Two big components of the plan call for moving first-line EMS supervisors from their cars to front-line ambulances, in the same manner that first-line fire supervisors work on front-line apparatus.  Currently, only 60% of NYCEMS personnel work on an ambulance.  Another component of the plan calls for battalion- based systems with three or four ambulances working collectively out of 64 stations to handle a geographic area.   Presently, EMS works collectively out of only 16 stations.
<P>  
   Supplementing the ambulances is the first responder program started earlier this year.  Currently the average response time for a first-due engine is less than five minutes, and with the merger, ambulance response times would be less than 10 minutes.
<P>      
     Commissioner Howard and Deputy Commissioner Dolan wish to recognize IAFF Local 94 and Local 854 of the Uniformed Fire Officer's for their strong support. 
<P>
<HR>     

More Excitement - Colonel David Abner, Executive Assistant Chief of the Louisville (KY) Fire Department informs us that Louisville EMS, a third service municipality, has been merged into LFD as a bureau.  The process started under retired Chief Russ Sanders and continued under the present chief, John Corso.  To start the process, LFD began training firefighters as EMTS three years ago.  Additionally, anybody graduating from the academy had to be certified as an EMT.  In January of 1994, LFD began running first responder calls and expects to have AEDs aboard the engines soon.  Louisville EMS personnel have received 400 hours of "modified firefighter training."  In essence, they were issued personal protective gear and are trained for every aspect of firefighting except interior attacks.  Colonel Abner tells me the merger and the consolidation of the communication centers has benefited the community by improving service levels, at no additional cost.  Colonel Abner noted the strong positive support of the IAFF local in coordinating the merger.  You can reach Colonel Abner at 502-574-3701. 
<P>
<HR>   

More Excitement - Chief Tom Siegfried, last year's president of the IAFC tells me that beginning January 15, 1996, his department in Altamonte Springs, Florida will begin ALS transport.  In a head-to-head battle with remnants of CareLine, the Altamonte Springs City Commission voted 5 - 0 to have the fire department begin transport.  The Commission also voted 4 - 1 to encourage Seminole County as a whole to begin ALS transport.  In all, Seminole County will have more than 20 fire department staffed ALS transport vehicles to serve its citizens.  For the citizens, it's a double-win as the service improves while the average rate for transport will drop from $325 under a commercial (private) provider to $182 under a fire-based system.
<P>
<HR>        

More Excitement - The Portland (Maine) Fire Department under the direction of Fire Chief Joseph E. Thomas and EMS Section Member, EMS Chief Martin J. Jordan have received Maine's coveted "Service of the Year Award" for community service. The PFD provides a variety of community programs which helped favor them from among 228 other licensed services.  You can speak to Chief Jordan at 207-874-8406.
<P>
<HR>
     

More Excitement - Dr. Zeccardi, Deputy Commissioner of Emergency Medical Service for the Philadelphia FD tells me they have increased the number of ambulances on the street by 40% over the last calendar year.  After January 1st, Philadelphia FD will have 35 vehicles in operation while an additional 89 new paramedics will have been hired.
<P>
<HR>

Chief John Bergmann is proud of his recent accomplishments in Kansas City, Kansas.  His quagmire included a FSLA settlement and being told to cut his budget while increasing service simultaneously.  To accomplish this, all paramedics have been cross-trained to be firefighters and placed on the city's 18 engines, resulting in four man ALS engine companies.  ALS transport was contracted out to a public utility model to complement the single tier ALS system with ALS first response.  The average response time for a KCKFD paramedic/firefighter to any medical emergency is now 3 -5 minutes, at no additional cost to the city.
<P>
<HR>

It is not too late to register for Fire Rescue East '96.  A strong EMS agenda is planned for the January conference to be held in Tampa.  The itinerary includes nine EMS sessions including; "Electronic Collection of EMS Field Data", "Educating the Field Medic", "Quality Improvement Workshop", and "Transport of the Sick & Injured, Public or Private".  Fire Rescue East '96 runs from January 6 - 11, 1996.  For more information call Larry Scovotto at 904-676-2744.
<P>
<HR>

In the last column I told you about how the Salt Lake City Fire Department has made a proposal to upgrade the service delivered to its citizens by assuming the transport role of EMS.  Obviously, the owners of Gold Cross Ambulance, the current provider has objections to this plan.  To help their cause, as reported in The Salt Lake Tribune, there has been a total of over $10,250 known Gold Cross-related contributions to mayoral hopeful Rich McKeown.  Gold Cross stands to loose $200,000 a year if Salt Lake City decides to operate its own emergency ambulance service.
<P>
<HR> 

Picture this all too familiar scenario - firefighter/paramedics inside their engine house hear a siren coming down the street.  As they walk outside, they see a commercial (private) ambulance flying past their station, hands waving out the windows, lights flashing and sirens blaring.  Sound familiar?  Well for Chief Robert Brown, Jr. of Anderson Township Fire and Rescue Department near Cincinnati, Ohio it has happened too often and he is drawing a line in the sand.  Chief Brown tells me that the commercial provider, Medic One Ambulance Service has responded on numerous occasions into their Township in an emergency fashion.  Some calls were even to a nursing home facility directly across the street from an engine house with paramedics and an ambulance.
<P>  

Unfortunately, the commercial providers response times were sometimes over 15 minutes in duration to critical patients.  A series of letters has gone back and forth including one from Medic One's attorney that says "immediately cease your interference with Medic One's `business` relationship with Salem Parke Nursing Home."  It is sad!  This sentence summed it all up - business first, patient care last.  Chief Brown tells me that is not a private versus public issue - he feels it is a patient care issue.  Chief Brown has formed a Task Force with management and IAFF Local 3111 to deal with this issue.  Best of all, he has the support of the citizens and the city council.  You can contact Chief Brown at 513-474- 5562.
<P>     
<HR>
Anyone interested in sitting on the nominating committee for the election of officers for the EMS section should contact Chief Mary Beth Michos at 703-792-6806.
<P>      
Thanks to Paul Casey, Norm Rynning, Fred Thorp, Alec Jensen, Bob Leonard, Larry Foster, Stan Human, Gary Creek for information provided.
<P>   
<HR>
Gary G. Ludwig is on the Executive Board of the EMS Section and is with the St. Louis Fire Department, responsible for EMS and communications.  He can be reached at 314-533-4175; fax 314-289-1977; AOL at GaryLudwig; or LUDWIGSTLFD on ICHIEFS.
<P>
