<HEAD>
<TITLE>Firefighters Turned Arsonists</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>FIREFIGHTERS TURNED ARSONISTS...</H3>
<P>
By Steve Macko
<P>
(ENN) Nov. 17, 1995--A Federal Bureau of Investigation study of 25 cases of firefighter
arson in seven U.S. states and one Canadian province recently found 
that the number one motive was for excitement -- especially among young
firefighters who were eager to put their training to practical use
and been seen as heroes to fellow firefighters.  In the study, 66
men were found to be responsible for setting 182 fires.
<P>

In the State of South Carolina, for example, there were 40 arrests of
firefighters for the crime of arson in 1994.  An executive director
of the South Carolina Insurance News Service said, "This is not an
uncommon thing across the country.  Sometimes there is a tendency ...
that they get the bug to set one so they can go ahead and put it out."
<P>
Then there is the interesting story from a rural area in South Carolina.
Recently five members of the Arkwright Volunteer Fire Department have
been arrested for allegedly setting about 150 fires between 1991 and
1993.  The suspicious fires only involved vacant buildings or land
and reportedly caused no injuries.
<P>
The fire chief of the department, Vincent Sherbert, said that before
the five men were arrested, there was something about them that bothered
him.  Sherbert said, "Sometimes when we'd get an alarm at midnight, they
would be at the station."  What was unusual is that some of the men,
two of them former chiefs and one a former captain, lived as much as
20 minutes away from the fire station.
<P>
Authorities said that they believed that the motive for the arson fires 
was a desire to practice their firefighting skills.  The five suspects are currently
out on bail and all have left the volunteer department.
<P>
Some fire experts have expressed concern that with a decreasing number of fires, nationwide, that this trend of firefighter-caused arson fires may increase. They say that examples of the behavior have been reported in too many places for it
to be an abberation in the statistics.
<P> 
<A HREF="/firepage.htm"><B>Return to the News Page</B></A>
</BODY>
