<HEAD>
<TITLE>NYC-EMS Supervisor Injured</TITLE>
<!-- Comment Here -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
Nov. 12, 1995
<BR>
EmergencyNet News
<P>

<H2> NYC-EMS SUPERVISOR CRITICALLY INJURED</H2>
<H3> Bad weather contributes to accident</H3>
<P>
                            By James J. Fay
<P>
     Deputy Chief Michael Rice of NYC*EMS is in very serious condition in New

York City's Jamaica Hospilal, as a result of injuries sustained from a one-car automobile

accident while enroute to John F. Kennedy International Airport. Rice, 43, was

responding to a fire reported on-board an incoming plane to JFK.
<P>

     The accident occurred on the Cross Island Parkway in the NYC Borough of

Queens during the earlier morning hours on Sunday, November 12th, during a heavy rain

and wind storm that covered the area during the weekend. Rice's marked EMS vehicle

was discovered by another EMS supervisor that was also responding to the airport

incident.
<P>

     Latest reports state that Rice has a fractured skull as well as other injuries.
<P>

     The fire on board the plane was in a microwave oven, and extinguished by plane

personnel.
<P>
ENN sends it's prayers and best wishes for Chief Rice and his family.
<BR>
<P>
